# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: quantum-computing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] In quantum mechanics and computing, the **Bloch sphere** is a geometrical representation of the pure state space of a two-level quantum mechanical system (qubit), named after the physicist Felix Bloch.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] Mathematically each quantum mechanical system is associated with a separable complex Hilbert space H .
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] A pure state of a quantum system is represented by a non-zero vector $\psi$ in H .
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] The vectors $\psi$ and $\lambda \psi$ (with $\lambda$ a non-zero complex number) represent the same state.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] A system with *n* mutually orthogonal quantum states can be described by a Hilbert space of dimension *n*.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] Pure states can be represented as equivalence classes, or, *rays* in a projective Hilbert space $\mathbf {P} (H_{n})=\mathbb {C} \mathbf {P} ^{n-1}$ .
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] For a two-dimensional Hilbert space, the space of all such states is the complex projective line $\mathbb {C} \mathbf {P} ^{1}.$ This is the Bloch sphere, which can be mapped to the Riemann sphere.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] The Bloch sphere is a unit 2-sphere, with antipodal points corresponding to a pair of mutually orthogonal state vectors.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] The north and south poles of the Bloch sphere are typically chosen to correspond to the standard basis vectors $|0\rangle$ and $|1\rangle$ , respectively, which in turn might correspond e.g. to the spin-up and spin-down states of an electron.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] The points on the surface of the sphere correspond to the pure states of the system, whereas the interior points correspond to the mixed states.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] The Bloch sphere may be generalized to an *n*-level quantum system, but then the visualization is less useful.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] The natural metric on the Bloch sphere is the Fubini–Study metric.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] The mapping from the unit 3-sphere in the two-dimensional state space $\mathbb {C} ^{2}$ to the Bloch sphere is the Hopf fibration, with each ray of spinors mapping to one point on the Bloch sphere.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] Given an orthonormal basis, any pure state $|\psi \rangle$ of a two-level quantum system can be written as a superposition of the basis vectors $|0\rangle$ and $|1\rangle$ , where the coefficient of (or contribution from) each of the two basis vectors is a complex number.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] This means that the state is described by four real numbers.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] However, only the relative phase between the coefficients of the two basis vectors has any physical meaning (the phase of the quantum system is not directly measurable), so that there is redundancy in this description.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] We can take the coefficient of $|0\rangle$ to be real and non-negative.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] This allows the state to be described by only three real numbers, giving rise to the three dimensions of the Bloch sphere.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] The representation is always unique, because, even though the value of $\phi$ is not unique when $|\psi \rangle$ is one of the states (see Bra-ket notation) $|0\rangle$ or $|1\rangle$ , the point represented by $\theta$ and $\phi$ is unique.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] on the unit sphere in $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ .
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] For mixed states, one considers the density operator.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] It is this vector that indicates the point within the sphere that corresponds to a given mixed state.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] Specifically, as a basic feature of the Pauli vector, the eigenvalues of ρ are ${\frac {1}{2}}\left(1\pm |{\vec {a}}|\right)$ .
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] Density operators must be positive-semidefinite, so it follows that $\left|{\vec {a}}\right|\leq 1$ .
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] As a consequence, the surface of the Bloch sphere represents all the pure states of a two-dimensional quantum system, whereas the interior corresponds to all the mixed states.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] This basis is often used in laser theory, where w is known as the population inversion.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] In this basis, the values $u,v,w$ are the expectations of the three Pauli matrices $X,Y,Z$ , allowing one to identify the three coordinates with x y and z axes.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] Consider an *n*-level quantum mechanical system.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] This system is described by an *n*-dimensional Hilbert space *H**n*.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] The pure state space is by definition the set of rays of *H**n*.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] To prove this fact, note that there is a natural group action of U(*n*) on the set of states of *H**n*.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] This action is continuous and transitive on the pure states.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] In linear algebra terms, this can be justified as follows.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] Any g of U(*n*) that leaves $|\psi \rangle$ invariant must have $|\psi \rangle$ as an eigenvector.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] Since the corresponding eigenvalue must be a complex number of modulus 1, this gives the U(1) factor of the isotropy group.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] The other part of the isotropy group is parametrized by the unitary matrices on the orthogonal complement of $|\psi \rangle$ , which is isomorphic to U(*n* − 1).
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] From this the assertion of the theorem follows from basic facts about transitive group actions of compact groups.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] The important fact to note above is that the *unitary group acts transitively* on pure states.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] Now the (real) dimension of U(*n*) is *n*2.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] is a local homeomorphism from the space of self-adjoint complex matrices to U(*n*).
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] The space of self-adjoint complex matrices has real dimension *n*2.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] Let us apply this to consider the real dimension of an *m* qubit quantum register.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] The corresponding Hilbert space has dimension 2*m*.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] Mathematically the Bloch sphere for a two-spinor state can be mapped to a Riemann sphere $\mathbb {C} \mathbf {P} ^{1}$ , i.e., the projective Hilbert space $\mathbf {P} (H_{2})$ with the 2-dimensional complex Hilbert space $H_{2}$ a representation space of SO(3).
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] If the Bloch sphere is thought of as being embedded in $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ with its center at the origin and with radius one, then the plane *z* = 0 (which intersects the Bloch sphere at a great circle; the sphere's equator, as it were) can be thought of as an Argand diagram.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] Plot point *u* in this plane — so that in $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ it has coordinates $(u_{x},u_{y},0)$ .
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] Draw a straight line through *u* and through the point on the sphere that represents $\left|\downarrow \right\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] (Let (0,0,1) represent $\left|\uparrow \right\rangle$ and (0,0,−1) represent $\left|\downarrow \right\rangle$ .) This line intersects the sphere at another point besides $\left|\downarrow \right\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] (The only exception is when $u=\infty$ , i.e., when $\alpha =0$ and $\beta \neq 0$ .) Call this point *P*.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] Point *u* on the plane *z* = 0 is the stereographic projection of point *P* on the Bloch sphere.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] The vector with tail at the origin and tip at *P* is the direction in 3-D space corresponding to the spinor $\left|\nearrow \right\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] Formulations of quantum mechanics in terms of pure states are adequate for isolated systems; in general quantum mechanical systems need to be described in terms of density operators.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] The Bloch sphere parametrizes not only pure states but mixed states for 2-level systems.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] where $p_{i}$ is the probability of the individual states within the ensemble and $x_{i},y_{i},z_{i}$ are the coordinates of the individual states (on the *surface* of Bloch sphere).
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] For states of higher dimensions there is difficulty in extending this to mixed states.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] The topological description is complicated by the fact that the unitary group does not act transitively on density operators.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] It is possible to generalize the construction of the Bloch ball to dimensions larger than 2, but the geometry of such a "Bloch body" is more complicated than that of a ball.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] A useful advantage of the Bloch sphere representation is that the evolution of the qubit state is describable by rotations of the Bloch sphere.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] The most concise explanation for why this is the case is that the Lie algebra for the group of unitary and hermitian matrices $SU(2)$ is isomorphic to the Lie algebra of the group of three dimensional rotations $SO(3)$ .
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] An interesting thing to note is that this expression is identical under relabelling to the extended Euler formula for pure imaginary quaternions.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] Ballentine presents an intuitive derivation for the infinitesimal unitary transformation.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] This is important for understanding why the rotations of Bloch spheres are exponentials of linear combinations of Pauli matrices.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] Hence a brief treatment on this is given here.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] A more complete description in a quantum mechanical context can be found here.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] Consider a family of unitary operators U representing a rotation about some axis.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] We define the infinitesimal unitary as the Taylor expansion truncated at second order.
[src:quantum-computing/bloch-sphere] where K is any Hermitian transformation, and is called the generator of the unitary family.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] In physics, the **no-cloning theorem** states that it is impossible to create an independent and identical copy of an arbitrary unknown quantum state, a statement which has profound implications in the field of quantum computing among others.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] The theorem is an evolution of the 1970 no-go theorem authored by James L.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] Park, in which he demonstrates that a non-disturbing measurement scheme which is both simple and perfect cannot exist (the same result would be independently derived in 1982 by William Wootters and Wojciech H.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] Zurek as well as Dennis Dieks the same year).
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] The aforementioned theorems do not preclude the state of one system becoming entangled with the state of another as cloning specifically refers to the creation of a separable state with identical factors.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] For example, one might use the controlled NOT gate and the Walsh–Hadamard gate to entangle two qubits without violating the no-cloning theorem as no well-defined state may be defined in terms of a subsystem of an entangled state.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] The no-cloning theorem (as generally understood) concerns only pure states whereas the generalized statement regarding mixed states is known as the no-broadcast theorem.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] The no-cloning theorem has a time-reversed dual, the no-deleting theorem.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] However, Juan Ortigoso pointed out in 2018 that a complete proof along with an interpretation in terms of the lack of simple nondisturbing measurements in quantum mechanics was already delivered by Park in 1970.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] Suppose we have two quantum systems *A* and *B* with a common Hilbert space $H=H_{A}=H_{B}$ .
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] Suppose we want to have a procedure to copy the state $|\phi \rangle _{A}$ of quantum system *A*, over the state $|e\rangle _{B}$ of quantum system *B,* for any original state $|\phi \rangle _{A}$ (see bra–ket notation).
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] That is, beginning with the state $|\phi \rangle _{A}\otimes |e\rangle _{B}$ , we want to end up with the state $|\phi \rangle _{A}\otimes |\phi \rangle _{B}$ .
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] To make a "copy" of the state *A*, we combine it with system *B* in some unknown initial, or blank, state $|e\rangle _{B}$ independent of $|\phi \rangle _{A}$ , of which we have no prior knowledge.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] The state of the initial composite system is then described by the following tensor product: $|\phi \rangle _{A}\otimes |e\rangle _{B}.$ (in the following we will omit the $\otimes$ symbol and keep it implicit).
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] The no-cloning theorem answers the following question in the negative: Is it possible to construct a unitary operator *U*, acting on $H_{A}\otimes H_{B}=H\otimes H$ , under which the state the system B is in always evolves into the state the system A is in, *regardless* of the state system A is in?
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] The extra phase factor expresses the fact that a quantum-mechanical state defines a normalised vector in Hilbert space only up to a phase factor i.e. as an element of projectivised Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] To prove the theorem, we select an arbitrary pair of states $|\phi \rangle _{A}$ and $|\psi \rangle _{A}$ in the Hilbert space H .
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] This implies that either $|\langle \phi |\psi \rangle |=1$ or $|\langle \phi |\psi \rangle |=0$ .
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] Hence by the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality either $|\phi \rangle =e^{i\beta }|\psi \rangle$ or $|\phi \rangle$ is orthogonal to $|\psi \rangle$ .
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] However, this cannot be the case for two *arbitrary* states.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] Therefore, a single universal *U* cannot clone a *general* quantum state.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] It can be represented by two complex numbers, called probability amplitudes (normalised to 1), that is three real numbers (two polar angles and one radius).
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] Copying three numbers on a classical computer using any copy and paste operation is trivial (up to a finite precision) but the problem manifests if the qubit is unitarily transformed (e.g. by the Hadamard quantum gate) to be polarised (which unitary transformation is a surjective isometry).
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] In such a case the qubit can be represented by just two real numbers (one polar angle and one radius equal to 1), while the value of the third can be arbitrary in such a representation.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] Yet a realisation of a qubit (polarisation-encoded photon, for example) is capable of storing the whole qubit information support within its "structure".
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] Thus no single universal unitary evolution *U* can clone an arbitrary quantum state according to the no-cloning theorem.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] It would have to depend on the transformed qubit (initial) state and thus would not have been *universal*.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] In the statement of the theorem, two assumptions were made: the state to be copied is a pure state and the proposed copier acts via unitary time evolution.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] These assumptions cause no loss of generality.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] If the state to be copied is a mixed state, it can be "purified," i.e. treated as a pure state of a larger system.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] Alternately, a different proof can be given that works directly with mixed states; in this case, the theorem is often known as the no-broadcast theorem.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] Similarly, an arbitrary quantum operation can be implemented via introducing an ancilla and performing a suitable unitary evolution.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] Thus the no-cloning theorem holds in full generality.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] Even though it is impossible to make perfect copies of an unknown quantum state, it is possible to produce imperfect copies.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] This can be done by coupling a larger auxiliary system to the system that is to be cloned, and applying a unitary transformation to the combined system.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] If the unitary transformation is chosen correctly, several components of the combined system will evolve into approximate copies of the original system.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] Hillery showed that a universal cloning machine can make a clone of an unknown state with the surprisingly high fidelity of 5/6.
[src:quantum-computing/no-cloning-theorem] Imperfect quantum cloning can be used as an eavesdropping attack on quantum cryptography protocols, among other uses in quantum information science.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] In quantum information theory, a **quantum circuit** is a model for quantum computation, similar to classical circuits, in which a computation is a sequence of quantum gates, measurements, initializations of qubits to known values, and possibly other actions.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] The minimum set of actions that a circuit needs to be able to perform on the qubits to enable quantum computation is known as DiVincenzo's criteria.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Circuits are written such that the horizontal axis is time, starting at the left hand side and ending at the right.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Horizontal lines are qubits, doubled lines represent classical bits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] The items that are connected by these lines are operations performed on the qubits, such as measurements or gates.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] These lines define the sequence of events, and are usually not physical cables.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] The graphical depiction of quantum circuit elements is described using a variant of the Penrose graphical notation.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Richard Feynman used an early version of the quantum circuit notation in 1986.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Most elementary logic gates of a classical computer are not reversible.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Thus, for instance, for an AND gate one cannot always recover the two input bits from the output bit; for example, if the output bit is 0, we cannot tell from this whether the input bits are 01 or 10 or 00.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] However, reversible gates in classical computers are easily constructed for bit strings of any length; moreover, these are actually of practical interest, since irreversible gates must always increase physical entropy.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] A reversible gate is a reversible function on *n*-bit data that returns *n*-bit data, where an *n*-bit data is a string of bits *x*1,*x*2, ...,*x**n* of length *n*.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] The set of *n*-bit data is the space {0,1}*n*, which consists of 2*n* strings of 0's and 1's.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] More precisely: an *n*-bit reversible gate is a bijective mapping *f* from the set {0,1}*n* of *n*-bit data onto itself.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] An example of such a reversible gate *f* is a mapping that applies a fixed permutation to its inputs.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] For reasons of practical engineering, one typically studies gates only for small values of *n*, e.g.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] These gates can be easily described by tables.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] The quantum logic gates are reversible unitary transformations on at least one qubit.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Multiple qubits taken together are referred to as quantum registers.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] To define quantum gates, we first need to specify the quantum replacement of an *n*-bit datum.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] This is by definition the space of complex-valued functions on {0,1}*n* and is naturally an inner product space. $\ell ^{2}$ means the function is a square-integrable function.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] This space can also be regarded as consisting of linear combinations, or superpositions, of classical bit strings.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Note that *H*QB(*n*) is a vector space over the complex numbers of dimension 2*n*.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] The elements of this vector space are the possible state-vectors of *n*-qubit quantum registers.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] is a special *n*-qubit register corresponding to the function which maps this classical bit string to 1 and maps all other bit strings to 0; these 2*n* special *n*-qubit registers are called *computational basis states*.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] All *n*-qubit registers are complex linear combinations of these computational basis states.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Quantum logic gates, in contrast to classical logic gates, are always reversible.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] One requires a special kind of reversible function, namely a unitary mapping, that is, a linear transformation of a complex inner product space that preserves the Hermitian inner product.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] An *n*-qubit (reversible) quantum gate is a unitary mapping *U* from the space *H*QB(*n*) of *n*-qubit registers onto itself.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Typically, we are only interested in gates for small values of *n*.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Note that *W**f* permutes the computational basis states.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Of particular importance is the controlled NOT gate (also called CNOT gate) *W*CNOT defined on a quantized 2 qubit.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Other examples of quantum logic gates derived from classical ones are the Toffoli gate and the Fredkin gate.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] However, the Hilbert-space structure of the qubits permits many quantum gates that are not induced by classical ones.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Again, we consider first *reversible* classical computation.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Conceptually, there is no difference between a reversible *n*-bit circuit and a reversible *n*-bit logic gate: either one is just an invertible function on the space of *n* bit data.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] However, as mentioned in the previous section, for engineering reasons we would like to have a small number of simple reversible gates, that can be put together to assemble any reversible circuit.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] To explain this assembly process, suppose we have a reversible *n*-bit gate *f* and a reversible *m*-bit gate *g*.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Putting them together means producing a new circuit by connecting some set of *k* outputs of *f* to some set of *k* inputs of *g* as in the figure below.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] The resulting circuit is also reversible and operates on *n*+*m*−*k* bits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] We will refer to this scheme as a *classical assemblage* (This concept corresponds to a technical definition in Kitaev's pioneering paper cited below).
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] In composing these reversible machines, it is important to ensure that the intermediate machines are also reversible.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] This condition assures that *intermediate* "garbage" is not created (the net physical effect would be to increase entropy, which is one of the motivations for going through this exercise).
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Note that each horizontal line on the above picture represents either 0 or 1, not these probabilities.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Since quantum computations are reversible, at each 'step' the number of lines must be the same number of input lines.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Also, each input combination must be mapped to a single combination at each 'step'.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] This means that each intermediate combination in a quantum circuit is a bijective function of the input.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Now it is possible to show that the Toffoli gate is a universal gate.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Notice that the result always has a string of *m* zeros as the ancilla bits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] No "rubbish" is ever produced, and so this computation is indeed one that, in a physical sense, generates no entropy.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] This issue is carefully discussed in Kitaev's article.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] More generally, any function *f* (bijective or not) can be simulated by a circuit of Toffoli gates.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Obviously, if the mapping fails to be injective, at some point in the simulation (for example as the last step) some "garbage" has to be produced.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] For quantum circuits a similar composition of qubit gates can be defined.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] That is, associated to any *classical assemblage* as above, we can produce a reversible quantum circuit when in place of *f* we have an *n*-qubit gate *U* and in place of *g* we have an *m*-qubit gate *W*.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] The fact that connecting gates this way gives rise to a unitary mapping on *n*+*m*−*k* qubit space is easy to check.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] In a real quantum computer the physical connection between the gates is a major engineering challenge, since it is one of the places where decoherence may occur.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] There are also universality theorems for certain sets of well-known gates; such a universality theorem exists, for instance, for the pair consisting of the single qubit phase gate *U*θ mentioned above (for a suitable value of θ), together with the 2-qubit CNOT gate *W*CNOT.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] However, the universality theorem for the quantum case is somewhat weaker than the one for the classical case; it asserts only that any reversible *n*-qubit circuit can be *approximated* arbitrarily well by circuits assembled from these two elementary gates.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Note that there are uncountably many possible single qubit phase gates, one for every possible angle θ, so they cannot all be represented by a finite circuit constructed from {*U*θ, *W*CNOT}.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] So far we have not shown how quantum circuits are used to perform computations.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Since many important numerical problems reduce to computing a unitary transformation *U* on a finite-dimensional space (the celebrated discrete Fourier transform being a prime example), one might expect that some quantum circuit could be designed to carry out the transformation *U*.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] In principle, one needs only to prepare an *n* qubit state ψ as an appropriate superposition of computational basis states for the input and measure the output *U*ψ.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] This does not prevent quantum circuits for the discrete Fourier transform from being used as intermediate steps in other quantum circuits, but the use is more subtle.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] In fact quantum computations are *probabilistic*.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] We now provide a mathematical model for how quantum circuits can simulate *probabilistic* but classical computations.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Consider an *r*-qubit circuit *U* with register space *H*QB(*r*).
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] The contents *x* = *x*1, ..., *x**m* of the classical input register are used to initialize the qubit register in some way.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] where there are *r*-*m* underbraced zeroed inputs.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Nevertheless, this perfect initialization is completely unrealistic.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Let us assume therefore that the initialization is a mixed state given by some density operator *S* which is near the idealized input in some appropriate metric, e.g.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Similarly, the output register space is related to the qubit register, by a *Y* valued observable *A*.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Note that observables in quantum mechanics are usually defined in terms of *projection valued measures* on **R**; if the variable happens to be discrete, the projection valued measure reduces to a family {Eλ} indexed on some parameter λ ranging over a countable set.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] on *Y* can be used to determine *F*(*x*) with an arbitrarily small probability of error by majority sampling, for a sufficiently large sample size.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] Specifically, take *k* independent samples from the probability distribution Pr on *Y* and choose a value on which more than half of the samples agree.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-circuit] This follows by applying the Chernoff bound.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] A **quantum computer** is a real or theoretical computer that exploits quantum phenomena like superposition and entanglement in an essential way.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] It is widely believed that a quantum computer could perform *some* calculations exponentially faster than any classical computer.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] For example, a large-scale quantum computer could break some widely used encryption schemes and aid physicists in performing physical simulations.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] However, current hardware implementations of quantum computation are largely experimental and only suitable for specialized tasks.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] The basic unit of information in quantum computing, the qubit (or "quantum bit"), serves the same function as the bit in ordinary or "classical" computing.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] However, unlike a classical bit, which can be in one of two states (a binary), a qubit can exist in a linear combination of two states known as a quantum superposition.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] The result of measuring a qubit is one of the two states given by a probabilistic rule.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] If a quantum computer manipulates the qubit in a particular way, wave interference effects amplify the probability of the desired measurement result.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] The design of quantum algorithms involves creating procedures that allow a quantum computer to perform this amplification.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum computers are not yet practical for real-world applications.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Physically engineering high-quality qubits has proven to be challenging.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] If a physical qubit is not sufficiently isolated from its environment, it suffers from quantum decoherence, introducing noise into calculations.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] National governments have invested heavily in experimental research aimed at developing scalable qubits with longer coherence times and lower error rates.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Example implementations include superconductors (which isolate an electrical current by eliminating electrical resistance) and ion traps (which confine a single atomic particle using electromagnetic fields).
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Researchers have claimed, and are widely believed to be correct, that certain quantum devices can outperform classical computers on narrowly defined tasks, a milestone referred to as quantum advantage or quantum supremacy.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] These tasks are not necessarily useful for real-world applications.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] As a result, current demonstrations are best understood as scientific milestones rather than evidence of broad near-term deployment.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] In December 2024, Google's Willow chip achieved below-threshold error correction, a milestone 30 years in the making, while global government investment in quantum computing reached $10 billion by April 2025.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] For many years, the fields of quantum mechanics and computer science formed distinct academic communities.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Modern quantum theory was developed in the 1920s to explain perplexing physical phenomena observed at atomic scales, and digital computers emerged in the following decades to replace human computers for tedious calculations.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Both disciplines had practical applications during World War II; computers played a major role in wartime cryptography, and quantum physics was essential for nuclear physics used in the Manhattan Project.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] As physicists applied quantum mechanical models to computational problems and swapped digital bits for qubits, the fields of quantum mechanics and computer science began to converge.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] In 1980, Paul Benioff introduced the quantum Turing machine, which uses quantum theory to describe a simplified computer.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] When digital computers became faster, physicists faced an exponential increase in overhead when simulating quantum dynamics, prompting Yuri Manin and Richard Feynman to independently suggest that hardware based on quantum phenomena might be more efficient for computer simulation.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] In a 1984 paper, Charles Bennett and Gilles Brassard applied quantum theory to cryptography protocols and demonstrated that quantum key distribution could enhance information security.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum algorithms then emerged for solving oracle problems, such as Deutsch's algorithm in 1985, the Bernstein–Vazirani algorithm in 1993, and Simon's algorithm in 1994.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] These algorithms did not solve practical problems, but demonstrated mathematically that one could obtain more information by querying a black box with a quantum state in superposition, sometimes referred to as *quantum parallelism*.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Peter Shor built on these results with his 1994 algorithm for breaking the widely used RSA and Diffie–Hellman encryption protocols, which drew significant attention to the field of quantum computing.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] In 1996, Grover's algorithm established a quantum speedup for the widely applicable unstructured search problem.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] The same year, Seth Lloyd proved that quantum computers could simulate quantum systems without the exponential overhead present in classical simulations, validating Feynman's 1982 conjecture.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Over the years, experimentalists have constructed small-scale quantum computers using trapped ions and superconductors.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] In 1998, a two-qubit quantum computer demonstrated the feasibility of the technology, and subsequent experiments have increased the number of qubits and reduced error rates.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Recent milestones in quantum computing have increasingly focused on controlling decoherence through quantum error correction.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] In 2024, researchers demonstrated theoretical and practical approaches for high threshold, low-overhead fault-tolerant quantum memory.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] These developments represent a critical step toward scaling systems beyond the noisy intermediate-scale quantum (NISQ) era into reliable, fault-tolerant computing architectures, though large-scale physical implementation remains an ongoing engineering challenge.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Computer engineers typically describe a modern computer's operation in terms of classical electrodynamics.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] In these "classical" computers, some components (such as semiconductors and random number generators) may rely on quantum behavior; however, because they are not isolated from their environment, any quantum information eventually quickly decoheres.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] While programmers may depend on probability theory when designing a randomized algorithm, quantum-mechanical notions such as superposition and wave interference are largely irrelevant in program analysis.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] The "classical" in *classical computation* thus refers to the computational model, not to whether the microscopic physics of the hardware is ultimately quantum-mechanical.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] A conventional digital computer can be described by classical states and transition rules: memory stores bits, while logic elements transform one configuration of bits into another.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] This computational behavior is not tied to electronics, and can be abstracted through the idea of a Turing machine, a mechanical device that performs deterministic transformations on a finite state.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] In principle, the same classical transition rules can be implemented by some entirely classical mechanical device, possibly with a fixed slow-down in physical time.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] If a classical computation uses randomness, this can be modeled as access to random classical bits rather than as coherent quantum information.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] A quantum computer, by contrast, uses coherent quantum states, so that superposition, relative phase, and interference are part of the computation itself, and has no classical counterpart.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum programs instead rely on precise control of coherent quantum systems.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Physicists describe these systems mathematically using linear algebra.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Complex numbers model probability amplitudes, vectors model quantum states, and matrices model the operations that can be performed on these states.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Programming a quantum computer is then a matter of composing operations in such a way that the resulting program computes a useful result in theory and is implementable in practice.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Just as the bit is the basic concept of classical information theory, the *qubit* is the fundamental unit of quantum information.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] The same term *qubit* is used to refer to an abstract mathematical model and to any physical system that is represented by that model.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] A classical bit, by definition, exists in either of two physical states, which can be denoted 0 and 1.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] A qubit is also described by a state, and two states, often written $|0\rangle$ and $|1\rangle$ , serve as the quantum counterparts of the classical states 0 and 1.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] However, the quantum states $|0\rangle$ and $|1\rangle$ belong to a vector space, meaning that they can be multiplied by constants and added together, and the result is again a valid quantum state.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Such a combination is known as a *superposition* of $|0\rangle$ and $|1\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] A two-dimensional vector mathematically represents a qubit state.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Physicists typically use bra–ket notation for quantum mechanical linear algebra, writing $|\psi \rangle$ 'ket psi' for a vector labeled $\psi$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Because a qubit is a two-state system, any qubit state takes the form $\alpha |0\rangle +\beta |1\rangle$ , where $|0\rangle$ and $|1\rangle$ are the standard *basis states*, and $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are the *probability amplitudes,* which are in general complex numbers.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] If either $\alpha$ or $\beta$ is zero, the qubit is effectively a classical bit; when both are nonzero, the qubit is in superposition.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Such a quantum state vector behaves similarly to a (classical) probability vector, with one key difference: unlike probabilities, probability *amplitudes* are not necessarily positive numbers.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Negative amplitudes allow for destructive wave interference.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] When a qubit is measured in the standard basis, the result is a classical bit.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] The Born rule describes the norm-squared correspondence between amplitudes and probabilities—when measuring a qubit $\alpha |0\rangle +\beta |1\rangle$ , the state collapses to $|0\rangle$ with probability $|\alpha |^{2}$ , or to $|1\rangle$ with probability $|\beta |^{2}$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Any valid qubit state has coefficients $\alpha$ and $\beta$ such that $|\alpha |^{2}+|\beta |^{2}=1$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] As an example, measuring the qubit $1/{\sqrt {2}}|0\rangle +1/{\sqrt {2}}|1\rangle$ would produce either $|0\rangle$ or $|1\rangle$ with equal probability.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Each additional qubit doubles the dimension of the state space.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] This vector inhabits a four-dimensional vector space spanned by the basis vectors |00⟩, |01⟩, |10⟩, and |11⟩.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] In general, the vector space for an n-qubit system is 2*n*-dimensional, and this makes it challenging for a classical computer to simulate a quantum one: representing a 100-qubit system requires storing 2100 classical values.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] The state of this one-qubit quantum memory can be manipulated by applying quantum logic gates, analogous to how classical memory can be manipulated with classical logic gates.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] One important gate for both classical and quantum computation is the NOT gate, which can be represented by a matrix $X:={\begin{pmatrix}0&1\\1&0\end{pmatrix}}.$ Mathematically, the application of such a logic gate to a quantum state vector is modeled with matrix multiplication.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] The mathematics of single-qubit gates can be extended to operate on multi-qubit quantum memories in two important ways.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] One way is simply to select a qubit and apply that gate to the target qubit while leaving the remainder of the memory unaffected.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Another way is to apply the gate to its target only if another part of the memory is in a desired state.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] These two choices can be illustrated using another example.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] In other words, the CNOT applies a NOT gate ( ${\textstyle X}$ from before) to the second qubit if and only if the first qubit is in the state ${\textstyle |1\rangle }$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] If the first qubit is ${\textstyle |0\rangle }$ , nothing is done to either qubit.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] In summary, quantum computation can be described as a network of quantum logic gates and measurements.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] However, any measurement can be deferred to the end of quantum computation, though this deferment may come at a computational cost, so most quantum circuits depict a network consisting only of quantum logic gates and no measurements.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] There are multiple models of computation for quantum computing, distinguished by the basic elements in which the computation is decomposed.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] A quantum gate array decomposes computation into a sequence of few-qubit quantum gates.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] A quantum computation can be described as a network of quantum logic gates and measurements.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Any quantum computation (which is, in the above formalism, any unitary matrix of size $2^{n}\times 2^{n}$ over n qubits) can be represented as a network of quantum logic gates from a fairly small family of gates.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] A choice of gate family that enables this construction is known as a universal gate set, since a computer that can run such circuits is a universal quantum computer.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] One common such set includes all single-qubit gates as well as the CNOT gate from above.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] This means any quantum computation can be performed by executing a sequence of single-qubit gates together with CNOT gates.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Though this gate set is infinite, it can be replaced with a finite gate set by appealing to the Solovay-Kitaev theorem.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Implementation of Boolean functions using the few-qubit quantum gates is presented here.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] A measurement-based quantum computer decomposes computation into a sequence of Bell state measurements and single-qubit quantum gates applied to a highly entangled initial state (a cluster state), using a technique called quantum gate teleportation.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] An adiabatic quantum computer, based on quantum annealing, decomposes computation into a slow continuous transformation of an initial Hamiltonian into a final Hamiltonian, whose ground states contain the solution.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Neuromorphic quantum computing (abbreviated 'n.quantum computing') is an unconventional process of computing that uses neuromorphic computing to perform quantum operations.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] It was suggested that quantum algorithms, which are algorithms that run on a realistic model of quantum computation, can be computed equally efficiently with neuromorphic quantum computing.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Both traditional quantum computing and neuromorphic quantum computing are physics-based unconventional computing approaches to computations and do not follow the von Neumann architecture.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] They both construct a system (a circuit) that represents the physical problem at hand and then leverage their respective physics properties of the system to seek the "minimum".
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Neuromorphic quantum computing and quantum computing share similar physical properties during computation.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] A topological quantum computer decomposes computation into the braiding of anyons in a 2D lattice.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] A quantum Turing machine is the quantum analog of a Turing machine.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] This equivalence need not hold for practical quantum computers, since the overhead of simulation may be too large to be practical.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] The threshold theorem shows how increasing the number of qubits can mitigate errors, yet fully fault-tolerant quantum computing remains "a rather distant dream".
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] According to some researchers, *noisy intermediate-scale quantum* (NISQ) machines may have specialized uses in the near future, but noise in quantum gates limits their reliability.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Scientists at Harvard University successfully created "quantum circuits" that correct errors more efficiently than alternative methods, which may potentially remove a major obstacle to practical quantum computers.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] The Harvard research team was supported by MIT, QuEra Computing, Caltech, and Princeton University and funded by DARPA's Optimization with Noisy Intermediate-Scale Quantum devices (ONISQ) program.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Digital cryptography enables communications to remain private, preventing unauthorized parties from accessing them.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Conventional encryption, the obscuring of a message with a key through an algorithm, relies on the algorithm being difficult to reverse.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Encryption is also the basis for digital signatures and authentication mechanisms.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum computing may be sufficiently more powerful that difficult reversals are feasible, allowing messages relying on conventional encryption to be read.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum cryptography replaces conventional algorithms with computations based on quantum computing.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] In principle, quantum encryption would be impossible to decode even with a quantum computer.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] This advantage comes at a significant cost in terms of elaborate infrastructure, while effectively preventing legitimate decoding of messages by governmental security officials.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Ongoing research in quantum and post-quantum cryptography has led to new algorithms for quantum key distribution, initial work on quantum random number generation and to some early technology demonstrations.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum cryptography enables new ways to transmit data securely; for example, quantum key distribution uses entangled quantum states to establish secure cryptographic keys.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] When a sender and receiver exchange quantum states, they can guarantee that an adversary does not intercept the message, as any unauthorized eavesdropper would disturb the delicate quantum system and introduce a detectable change.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] With appropriate cryptographic protocols, the sender and receiver can thus establish shared private information resistant to eavesdropping.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Modern fiber-optic cables can transmit quantum information over relatively short distances.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Ongoing experimental research aims to develop more reliable hardware (such as quantum repeaters), hoping to scale this technology to long-distance quantum networks with end-to-end entanglement.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Theoretically, this could enable novel technological applications, such as distributed quantum computing and enhanced quantum sensing.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum teleportation is a protocol by which Alice can transmit the quantum state of a qubit to Bob using one shared entangled pair (e-bit) and two classical bits of communication.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] The state of Alice's qubit is not physically transmitted—instead, it is reconstructed at Bob's end through classically communicated measurement outcomes and local unitary corrections.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] This demonstrates that quantum communication requires both entanglement and classical communication; neither alone is sufficient.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Teleportation cannot be used to transmit information faster than light because the classical bits must travel through normal channels.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Superdense coding is the complementary protocol: using one shared e-bit and sending only one qubit, Alice can transmit two classical bits to Bob.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] This appears to violate Holevo's theorem—which states that a single qubit can carry at most one bit of classical information—but the shared entanglement circumvents this limit.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Superdense coding thus demonstrates that entanglement can effectively double the classical information-carrying capacity of quantum communication.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Progress in finding quantum algorithms typically focuses on the quantum circuit model, though exceptions like the quantum adiabatic algorithm exist.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum algorithms can be roughly categorized by the type of speedup achieved over corresponding classical algorithms.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] These algorithms depend on the primitive of the quantum Fourier transform.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] No mathematical proof has been found that shows that an equally fast classical algorithm cannot be discovered, but evidence suggests that this is unlikely.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Certain oracle problems like Simon's problem and the Bernstein–Vazirani problem do give provable speedups, though this is in the quantum query model, which is a restricted model where lower bounds are much easier to prove and don't necessarily translate to speedups for practical problems.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Because these problems are BQP-complete, an equally fast classical algorithm for them would imply that "no quantum algorithm" provides a super-polynomial speedup, which is believed to be unlikely.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Some quantum algorithms, such as Grover's algorithm and amplitude amplification, give polynomial speedups over corresponding classical algorithms.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Though these algorithms give comparably modest quadratic speedup, they are widely applicable and thus give speedups for a wide range of problems.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] These speed-ups are, however, over the theoretical worst-case of classical algorithms, and concrete real-world speed-ups over algorithms used in practice have not been demonstrated.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Since chemistry and nanotechnology rely on understanding quantum systems, and such systems are impossible to simulate in an efficient manner classically, quantum simulation may be an important application of quantum computing.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Recent reviews identify quantum chemistry as one of the most promising application areas for quantum computing, particularly for problems in electronic structure, chemical dynamics, and spectroscopy, while noting that useful implementations remain limited by current hardware.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum simulation could also be used to simulate the behavior of atoms and particles at unusual conditions such as the reactions inside a collider.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] In June 2023, IBM computer scientists reported that a quantum computer produced better results for a physics problem than a conventional supercomputer.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] About 2% of the annual global energy output is used for nitrogen fixation to produce ammonia for the Haber process in the agricultural fertiliser industry (even though naturally occurring organisms also produce ammonia).
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum simulations might be used to understand this process and increase the energy efficiency of production.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] It is expected that an early use of quantum computing will be modeling that improves the efficiency of the Haber–Bosch process by the mid-2020s although some have predicted it will take longer.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] A notable application of quantum computing is in attacking cryptographic systems that are currently in use.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Integer factorization, which underpins the security of public key cryptographic systems, is believed to be computationally infeasible on a classical computer for large integers if they are the product of a few prime numbers (e.g., the product of two 300-digit primes).
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] By contrast, a quantum computer could solve this problem exponentially faster using Shor's algorithm to factor the integer.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] This ability would allow a quantum computer to break many of the cryptographic systems in use today, in the sense that there would be a polynomial time (in the number of digits of the integer) algorithm for solving the problem.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] In particular, most of the popular public key ciphers are based on the difficulty of factoring integers or the discrete logarithm problem, both of which can be solved by Shor's algorithm.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] In particular, the RSA, Diffie–Hellman, and elliptic curve Diffie–Hellman algorithms could be broken.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] These are used to protect secure Web pages, encrypted email, and many other types of data.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Breaking these would have significant ramifications for electronic privacy and security.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Identifying cryptographic systems that may be secure against quantum algorithms is an actively researched topic under the field of *post-quantum cryptography*.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Some public-key algorithms are based on problems other than the integer factorization and discrete logarithm problems to which Shor's algorithm applies, such as the McEliece cryptosystem, which relies on a hard problem in coding theory.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Lattice-based cryptosystems are also not known to be broken by quantum computers, and finding a polynomial time algorithm for solving the dihedral hidden subgroup problem, which would break many lattice-based cryptosystems, is a well-studied open problem.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] The most well-known example of a problem that allows for a polynomial quantum speedup is *unstructured search*, which involves finding a marked item out of a list of n items in a database.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] This can be solved by Grover's algorithm using $O({\sqrt {n}})$ queries to the database, quadratically fewer than the $\Omega (n)$ queries required for classical algorithms.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] In this case, the advantage is not only provable but also optimal: it has been shown that Grover's algorithm gives the maximal possible probability of finding the desired element for any number of oracle lookups.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Many examples of provable quantum speedups for query problems are based on Grover's algorithm, including Brassard, Høyer, and Tapp's algorithm for finding collisions in two-to-one functions, and Farhi, Goldstone, and Gutmann's algorithm for evaluating NAND trees.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] There exists a Boolean function that evaluates each input and determines whether it is the correct answer.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] For problems with all these properties, the running time of Grover's algorithm on a quantum computer scales as the square root of the number of inputs (or elements in the database), as opposed to the linear scaling of classical algorithms.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] A general class of problems to which Grover's algorithm can be applied is a Boolean satisfiability problem, where the *database* through which the algorithm iterates is that of all possible answers.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] An example and possible application of this is a password cracker that attempts to guess a password.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Breaking symmetric ciphers with this algorithm is of interest to government agencies.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum annealing uses the adiabatic theorem to perform calculations.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] A system is placed in the ground state for a simple Hamiltonian, which slowly evolves to a more complicated Hamiltonian whose ground state represents the solution to the problem in question.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] The adiabatic theorem states that if the evolution is slow enough, the system will stay in its ground state at all times through the process.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum annealing can solve Ising models and the (computationally equivalent) QUBO problem, which in turn can be used to encode a wide range of combinatorial optimization problems.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Adiabatic optimization may be helpful for solving computational biology problems.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Since quantum computers can produce outputs that classical computers cannot produce efficiently, and since quantum computation is fundamentally linear algebraic, some express hope in developing quantum algorithms that can speed up machine learning tasks.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] However, review literature notes that many proposed quantum machine-learning advantages rely on assumptions about efficient data encoding or continued access to quantum hardware, and have not yet translated into broad practical end-to-end advantage on current devices.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] For example, the HHL Algorithm, named after its discoverers Harrow, Hassidim, and Lloyd, is believed to provide speedup over classical counterparts.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Some research groups have recently explored the use of quantum annealing hardware for training Boltzmann machines and deep neural networks.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Deep generative chemistry models have been explored for potential applications in drug discovery.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Early experimental work has explored the use of near-term quantum hardware in molecular generative modeling for drug discovery.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] However, the immense size and complexity of the structural space of all possible drug-like molecules pose significant obstacles, which could be overcome in the future by quantum computers.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Quantum computers are naturally good for solving complex quantum many-body problems and thus may be instrumental in applications involving quantum chemistry.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Therefore, one can expect that quantum-enhanced generative models including quantum GANs may eventually be developed into ultimate generative chemistry algorithms.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] Artificial intelligence has also been explored as a tool for discovering and optimizing algorithms relevant to quantum computing.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] AlphaEvolve, a Google DeepMind system based on large language models and evolutionary algorithms, has been described as a coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p01] In quantum-computing research, AlphaEvolve-optimized quantum circuits have been used in work on quantum computation of molecular geometry through many-body nuclear spin echoes.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] As of 2023, classical computers outperform quantum computers for all real-world applications.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] While current quantum computers may speed up solutions to particular mathematical problems, they give no computational advantage for practical tasks.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Scientists and engineers are exploring multiple technologies for quantum computing hardware and hope to develop scalable quantum architectures, but serious obstacles remain.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] In practice, improvements in qubit counts alone are not enough, because error rates, connectivity, and data movement also affect whether an end-to-end application can outperform classical methods.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] There are a number of technical challenges in building a large-scale quantum computer.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] The control of multi-qubit systems requires the generation and coordination of a large number of electrical signals with tight and deterministic timing resolution.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] This has led to the development of quantum controllers that enable interfacing with the qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Scaling these systems to support a growing number of qubits is an additional challenge.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] The theoretical potential for large-scale quantum computers to eventually break widely used public-key encryption schemes has prompted significant motivated changes in global cybersecurity strategies.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] In response to this future challenge, organizations, including the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), have initiated detailed standardization processes for post-quantum cryptography.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] These global efforts are designed to develop, evaluate, and deploy cryptographic algorithms that remain safe against both quantum and classical computer attacks, well before fully fault-tolerant quantum systems become available.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Sourcing parts for quantum computers is also very difficult.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Superconducting quantum computers, like those constructed by Google and IBM, need helium-3, a nuclear research byproduct, and special superconducting cables made only by the Japanese company Coax Co.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] On 27 January 2026, the US DARPA agency made a call for proposals for a quantum computing coolant below 1 kelvin, which does not use helium-3.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] In February 2026, the Chinese Academy of Sciences announced the testing of a rare-earth alloy, EuCo2Al9, which could fill a similar role.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] One of the greatest challenges involved in constructing quantum computers is controlling or removing quantum decoherence.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] This usually means isolating the system from its environment, as interactions with the external world cause the system to decohere.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] However, other sources of decoherence also exist.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Examples include the quantum gates, the lattice vibrations, and the background thermonuclear spin of the physical system used to implement the qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Decoherence is irreversible, as it is effectively non-unitary, and is usually something that should be highly controlled, if not avoided.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Decoherence times for candidate systems in particular, the transverse relaxation time *T*2 (for NMR and MRI technology, also called the *dephasing time*), typically range between nanoseconds and seconds at low temperatures.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Currently, some quantum computers require their qubits to be cooled to 20 millikelvin (usually using a dilution refrigerator) in order to prevent significant decoherence.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] A 2020 study argues that ionizing radiation such as cosmic rays can nevertheless cause certain systems to decohere within milliseconds.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] As a result, time-consuming tasks may render some quantum algorithms inoperable, as attempting to maintain the state of qubits for a long enough duration will eventually corrupt the superpositions.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] These issues are more difficult for optical approaches as the timescales are orders of magnitude shorter, and an often-cited approach to overcoming them is optical pulse shaping.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Error rates are typically proportional to the ratio of operating time to decoherence time; hence, any operation must be completed much more quickly than the decoherence time.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] As described by the threshold theorem, if the error rate is small enough, it is thought to be possible to use quantum error correction to suppress errors and decoherence.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] This allows the total calculation time to be longer than the decoherence time if the error correction scheme can correct errors faster than decoherence introduces them.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] An often-cited figure for the required error rate in each gate for fault-tolerant computation is 10−3, assuming the noise is depolarizing.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Meeting this scalability condition is possible for a wide range of systems.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] However, the use of error correction brings with it the cost of a greatly increased number of required qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] The number required to factor integers using Shor's algorithm is still polynomial, and thought to be between L and *L*2, where L is the number of binary digits in the number to be factored; error correction algorithms would inflate this figure by an additional factor of L.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] For a 1000-bit number, this implies a need for about 104 bits without error correction.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] With error correction, the figure would rise to about 107 bits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Computation time is about *L*2 or about 107 steps and at 1 MHz, about 10 seconds.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] However, the encoding and error-correction overheads increase the size of a real fault-tolerant quantum computer by several orders of magnitude.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Careful estimates show that at least 3 million physical qubits would factor 2,048-bit integer in 5 months on a fully error-corrected trapped-ion quantum computer.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] In terms of the number of physical qubits, to date, this remains the lowest estimate for practically useful integer factorization problem sizing 1,024-bit or larger.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] One approach to overcoming errors combines low-density parity-check code with cat qubits that have intrinsic bit-flip error suppression.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Implementing 100 logical qubits with 768 cat qubits could reduce the error rate to one part in 108 per cycle per bit.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Another approach to the stability-decoherence problem is to create a topological quantum computer with anyons, quasi-particles used as threads, and relying on braid theory to form stable logic gates.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Non-Abelian anyons can, in effect, remember how they have been manipulated, making them potentially useful in quantum computing.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] As of 2025, Microsoft and other organizations are investing in quasi-particle research.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Physicist John Preskill coined the term *quantum supremacy* to describe the engineering feat of demonstrating that a programmable quantum device can solve a problem beyond the capabilities of state-of-the-art classical computers.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] The problem need not be useful, so some view the quantum supremacy test only as a potential future benchmark.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] In October 2019, Google AI Quantum, with the help of NASA, became the first to claim to have achieved quantum supremacy by performing calculations on the Sycamore quantum computer more than 3,000,000 times faster than they could be done on Summit, generally considered the world's fastest computer.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] In December 2020, a group at USTC implemented a type of boson sampling on 76 photons with a photonic quantum computer, Jiuzhang, to demonstrate quantum supremacy.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] The authors claim that a classical contemporary supercomputer would require a computational time of 600 million years to generate the number of samples their quantum processor can generate in 20 seconds.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Claims of quantum supremacy have generated hype around quantum computing, but they are based on contrived benchmark tasks that do not directly imply useful real-world applications.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Accordingly, benchmark-level quantum advantage should not be interpreted as proof that quantum computers are already broadly useful across practical computing workloads.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Despite high hopes for quantum computing, significant progress in hardware, and optimism about future applications, a 2023 Nature spotlight article summarized current quantum computers as being "For now, [good for] absolutely nothing".
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] The article elaborated that quantum computers are yet to be more useful or efficient than conventional computers in any case, though it also argued that, in the long term, such computers are likely to be useful.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] A 2023 Communications of the ACM article found that current quantum computing algorithms are "insufficient for practical quantum advantage without significant improvements across the software/hardware stack".
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] It argues that the most promising candidates for achieving speedup with quantum computers are "small-data problems", for example, in chemistry and materials science.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] This state of affairs can be traced to several current and long-term considerations.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] In particular, building computers with large numbers of qubits may be futile if those qubits are not connected well enough and cannot maintain a sufficiently high degree of entanglement for a long time.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] When trying to outperform conventional computers, quantum computing researchers often look for new tasks that can be solved on quantum computers, but this leaves the possibility that efficient non-quantum techniques will be developed in response, as seen for Quantum supremacy demonstrations.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Therefore, it is desirable to prove lower bounds on the complexity of best possible non-quantum algorithms (which may be unknown) and show that some quantum algorithms asymptotically improve upon those bounds.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Bill Unruh doubted the practicality of quantum computers in a paper published in 1994.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Paul Davies argued that a 400-qubit computer would even come into conflict with the cosmological information bound implied by the holographic principle.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Skeptics like Gil Kalai doubt that quantum supremacy will ever be achieved.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] continuously variable parameters defining the quantum state of such a system?
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] A practical quantum computer must use a physical system as a programmable quantum register.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Researchers are exploring several technologies as candidates for reliable qubit implementations.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Superconductors and trapped ions are some of the most developed proposals, but experimentalists are considering other hardware possibilities as well.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] For example, topological quantum computer approaches are being explored for more fault-tolerance computing systems.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] The first quantum logic gates were implemented with trapped ions and prototype general-purpose machines with up to 20 qubits have been realized.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] However, the technology behind these devices combines complex vacuum equipment, lasers, and microwave and radio frequency equipment, making full-scale processors difficult to integrate with standard computing equipment.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Moreover, the trapped ion system itself has engineering challenges to overcome.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] The largest commercial systems are based on superconductor devices and have scaled to 2000 qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] However, the error rates for larger machines have been on the order of 5%.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Technologically, these devices are all cryogenic and scaling to large numbers of qubits requires wafer-scale integration, a serious engineering challenge by itself.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] In addition to cryogenic platforms, room-temperature approaches to spin–photon interfaces have been experimentally demonstrated.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Such room-temperature, chip-integrated spin–photon interfaces are being investigated as potential building blocks for heterogeneous quantum networks that combine different qubit modalities and reduce reliance on large cryogenic infrastructures.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Any computational problem solvable by a classical computer is also solvable by a quantum computer.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Intuitively, this is because it is believed that all physical phenomena, including the operation of classical computers, can be described using quantum mechanics, which underlies the operation of quantum computers.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] Conversely, any problem solvable by a quantum computer is also solvable by a classical computer.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] It is possible to simulate both quantum and classical computers manually with just some paper and a pen, if given enough time.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] More formally, any quantum computer can be simulated by a Turing machine.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] In other words, quantum computers provide no additional power over classical computers in terms of computability.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] This means that quantum computers cannot solve undecidable problems like the halting problem, and the existence of quantum computers does not disprove the Church–Turing thesis.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] While quantum computers cannot solve any problems that classical computers cannot already solve, it is suspected that they can solve certain problems faster than classical computers.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] For instance, it is known that quantum computers can efficiently factor integers, while this is not believed to be the case for classical computers.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] The class of problems that can be efficiently solved by a quantum computer with bounded error is called BQP, for "bounded error, quantum, polynomial time".
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] More formally, BQP is the class of problems that can be solved by a polynomial-time quantum Turing machine with an error probability of at most 1/3.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] As a class of probabilistic problems, BQP is the quantum counterpart to BPP ("bounded error, probabilistic, polynomial time"), the class of problems that can be solved by polynomial-time probabilistic Turing machines with bounded error.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] It is known that ${\mathsf {BPP\subseteq BQP}}$ but there is no proof ${\mathsf {BQP\neq BPP}}$ , which intuitively would mean that quantum computers are more powerful than classical computers in terms of time complexity.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] The exact relationship of BQP to P, NP, and PSPACE is not known.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] It is further suspected that BQP is a strict superset of P, meaning that there exist problems that are efficiently solvable by quantum computers that are not efficiently solvable by deterministic classical computers.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] For instance, integer factorization and the discrete logarithm problem are known to be in BQP and are suspected to be outside of P.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] On the relationship of BQP to NP, little is known beyond the fact that some NP problems that are believed not to be in P are also in BQP (integer factorization and the discrete logarithm problem are both in NP, for example).
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] It is suspected that ${\mathsf {NP\nsubseteq BQP}}$ ; that is, it is believed that there are efficiently checkable problems that are not efficiently solvable by a quantum computer.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-computing-p02] As a direct consequence of this belief, it is also suspected that BQP is disjoint from the class of NP-complete problems (if an NP-complete problem were in BQP, then it would follow from NP-hardness that all problems in NP are in BQP).
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Measurements of physical properties such as position, momentum, spin, and polarization performed on entangled particles can, in some cases, be found to be perfectly correlated.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] For example, if a pair of entangled particles is generated such that their total spin is known to be zero, and one particle is found to have clockwise spin on a first axis, then the spin of the other particle, measured on the same axis, is found to be anticlockwise.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] This behavior gives rise to seemingly paradoxical effects: any measurement of a particle's properties results in an apparent and irreversible wave function collapse of that particle and changes the original quantum state.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] With entangled particles, such measurements affect the entangled system as a whole.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Such phenomena were the subject of a 1935 paper by Albert Einstein, Boris Podolsky, and Nathan Rosen, and several papers by Erwin Schrödinger shortly thereafter, describing what came to be known as the EPR paradox.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Einstein and others considered such behavior impossible, as it violated the local realism view of causality and argued that the accepted formulation of quantum mechanics must therefore be incomplete.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Later, the counterintuitive predictions of quantum mechanics were verified in tests where polarization or spin of entangled particles were measured at separate locations, statistically violating Bell's inequality.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] This established that the correlations produced from quantum entanglement cannot be explained in terms of local hidden variables.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Entanglement can produce statistical correlations between events in widely separated places, but it cannot be used for faster-than-light communication.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Quantum entanglement has been demonstrated experimentally with photons, electrons, top quarks, molecules and even small diamonds.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The use of quantum entanglement in communication and computation is an active area of research and development.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Albert Einstein and Niels Bohr engaged in a long-running collegial dispute over the interpretation of quantum mechanics, now known as the Bohr–Einstein debates.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] During these debates, Einstein introduced a thought experiment involving a box that emits a photon.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] He noted that the experimenter's choice of which measurement to make on the box would change what can be predicted about the photon, even when the photon is very far away.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] This argument, which Einstein had formulated by 1931, was an early recognition of what would later be called entanglement.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] That same year, Hermann Weyl observed in his textbook on group theory and quantum mechanics that quantum systems composed of multiple interacting parts exhibit a kind of *Gestalt,* in which "the whole is greater than the sum of its parts".
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In 1932, Erwin Schrödinger derived the defining equations of quantum entanglement but left them unpublished.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In 1935, Grete Hermann studied the mathematics of an electron interacting with a photon and noted the phenomenon that would later be called entanglement.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Later that same year, Einstein, Boris Podolsky and Nathan Rosen published a paper on what is now known as the Einstein–Podolsky–Rosen (EPR) paradox, a thought experiment that attempted to show that "the quantum-mechanical description of physical reality given by wave functions is not complete".
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Their thought experiment considered two systems that interact and then separate, and they argued that, afterward, quantum mechanics could not describe the two systems individually.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Shortly after this paper appeared, Erwin Schrödinger wrote a letter to Einstein in German in which he used the word *Verschränkung* (translated by himself as *entanglement*) to describe situations like that of the EPR scenario.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Einstein later disparaged quantum mechanics for seemingly exhibiting "*spukhafte Fernwirkung*", or "spooky action at a distance", meaning the acquisition of a value of a property at one location resulting from a measurement at a distant location.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In 1946, John Archibald Wheeler suggested studying the polarization of pairs of gamma-ray photons produced by electron–positron annihilation.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Chien-Shiung Wu and Irving Shaknov carried out this experiment in 1949, thereby demonstrating that the entangled particle pairs considered by EPR could be created in the laboratory.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Despite Schrödinger's claim of its importance, little work on entanglement was published for decades after his paper was published.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Bell demonstrated an upper limit, seen in Bell's inequality, regarding the strength of correlations that can be produced in any theory obeying local realism, and showed that quantum theory predicts violations of this limit for certain entangled systems.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] His inequality is experimentally testable, and there have been numerous relevant experiments, starting with the pioneering work of Stuart Freedman and John Clauser in 1972, and Alain Aspect's experiments in 1982.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] While Bell actively discouraged students from pursuing work like his as too esoteric, after a talk at Oxford a student named Artur Ekert suggested that the violation of a Bell inequality could be used as a resource for communication.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Ekert followed up by publishing a quantum key distribution protocol called E91 based on it.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In 1992, the entanglement concept was leveraged to propose quantum teleportation, an effect that was realized experimentally in 1997.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Beginning in the mid-1990s, Anton Zeilinger used the generation of entanglement via parametric down-conversion to develop entanglement swapping and demonstrate quantum cryptography with entangled photons.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In 2022, the Nobel Prize in Physics was awarded to Aspect, Clauser, and Zeilinger "for experiments with entangled photons, establishing the violation of Bell inequalities and pioneering quantum information science".
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Just as energy is a resource that facilitates mechanical operations, entanglement is a resource that facilitates performing tasks that involve communication and computation.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The mathematical definition of entanglement can be paraphrased as saying that maximal knowledge about the whole of a system does not imply maximal knowledge about the individual parts of that system.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] If the quantum state that describes a pair of particles is entangled, then the results of measurements upon one half of the pair can be strongly correlated with the results of measurements upon the other.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] However, entanglement is not the same as "correlation" as understood in classical probability theory and in daily life.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Instead, entanglement can be thought of as *potential* correlation that can be used to generate actual correlation in an appropriate experiment.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The correlations generated from an entangled quantum state cannot in general be replicated by classical probability.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] An example of entanglement is a subatomic particle that decays into an entangled pair of other particles.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] For instance, a spin-zero particle could decay into a pair of spin-1/2 particles.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] If there is no orbital angular momentum, the total spin angular momentum after this decay must be zero (by the conservation of angular momentum).
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Whenever the first particle is measured to be spin up on some axis, the other, when measured on the same axis, is always found to be spin down.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] This is called the spin anti-correlated case and the pair is said to be in the singlet state.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Perfect anti-correlations like this could be explained by "hidden variables" within the particles.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] For example, we could hypothesize that the particles are made in pairs such that one carries a value of "up" while the other carries a value of "down".
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Then, knowing the result of the spin measurement upon one particle, we could predict that the other will have the opposite value.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Bell illustrated this with a story about a colleague, Bertlmann, who always wore socks with mismatching colors.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Quantum systems can become entangled through various types of interactions.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] For some ways in which entanglement may be achieved for experimental purposes, see the section below on methods.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Entanglement is broken when the entangled particles decohere through interaction with the environment; for example, when a measurement is made.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In more detail, this process involves the particles becoming entangled with the environment, as a consequence of which, the quantum state describing the particles themselves is no longer entangled.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Mathematically, an entangled system can be defined to be one whose quantum state cannot be factored as a product of states of its local constituents; that is to say, they are not individual particles but are an inseparable whole.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] When entanglement is present, one constituent cannot be fully described without considering the other(s).
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The state of a composite system is always expressible as a sum, or superposition, of products of states of local constituents; it is entangled if this sum cannot be written as a single product term.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The singlet state described above is the basis for one version of the EPR paradox.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In this variant, introduced by David Bohm, a source emits particles and sends them in opposite directions.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The state describing each pair is entangled.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In the standard textbook presentation of quantum mechanics, performing a spin measurement on one of the particles causes the wave function for the whole pair to collapse into a state in which each particle has a definite spin (either up or down) along the axis of measurement.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The outcome is random, with each possibility having a probability of 50%.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] However, if both spins are measured along the same axis, they are found to be anti-correlated.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] This means that the random outcome of the measurement made on one particle seems to have been transmitted to the other, so that it can make the "right choice" when it too is measured.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The distance and timing of the measurements can be chosen so as to make the interval between the two measurements spacelike, hence, any causal effect connecting the events would have to travel faster than light.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] According to the principles of special relativity, it is not possible for any information to travel between two such measuring events.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] It is not even possible to say which of the measurements came first.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] For two spacelike separated events *x*1 and *x*2 there are inertial frames in which *x*1 is first and others in which *x*2 is first.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Therefore, the correlation between the two measurements cannot be explained as one measurement determining the other: different observers would disagree about the role of cause and effect.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] A possible resolution to the paradox is to assume that quantum theory is incomplete, and the result of measurements depends on predetermined "hidden variables".
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The state of the particles being measured contains some hidden variables, whose values effectively determine, right from the moment of separation, what the outcomes of the spin measurements are going to be.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] This would mean that each particle carries all the required information with it, and nothing needs to be transmitted from one particle to the other at the time of measurement.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Einstein and others originally believed this was the only way out of the paradox, and the accepted quantum mechanical description (with a random measurement outcome) must be incomplete.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Local hidden variable theories fail when measurements of the spin of entangled particles along different axes are considered.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] If a large number of pairs of such measurements are made (on a large number of pairs of entangled particles), then statistically, if the local realist or hidden variables view were correct, the results would always satisfy Bell's inequality.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] A number of experiments have shown in practice that Bell's inequality is not satisfied.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Moreover, when measurements of the entangled particles are made in moving relativistic reference frames, in which each measurement (in its own relativistic time frame) occurs before the other, the measurement results remain correlated.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The fundamental issue about measuring spin along different axes is that these measurements cannot have definite values at the same time―they are incompatible in the sense that these measurements' maximum simultaneous precision is constrained by the uncertainty principle.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] This is contrary to what is found in classical physics, where any number of properties can be measured simultaneously with arbitrary accuracy.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] It has been proven mathematically that compatible measurements cannot show Bell-inequality-violating correlations, and thus entanglement is a fundamentally non-classical phenomenon.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] As discussed above, entanglement is necessary to produce a violation of a Bell inequality.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] However, the mere presence of entanglement alone is insufficient, as Bell himself noted in his 1964 paper.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] This is demonstrated, for example, by Werner states, which are a family of states describing pairs of particles.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] For appropriate choices of the key parameter that identifies a given Werner state within the full set thereof, the Werner states exhibit entanglement.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Yet pairs of particles described by Werner states always admit a local hidden variable model.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In other words, these states cannot power the violation of a Bell inequality, despite possessing entanglement.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] This can be generalized from pairs of particles to larger collections as well.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The violation of Bell inequalities is often called *quantum nonlocality.* This term is not without controversy.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] It is sometimes argued that using the term *nonlocality* carries the unwarranted implication that the violation of Bell inequalities must be explained by physical, faster-than-light signals.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In other words, the failure of local hidden-variable models to reproduce quantum mechanics is not necessarily a sign of true nonlocality in quantum mechanics itself.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Despite these reservations, the term *nonlocality* has become a widespread convention.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The term *nonlocality* is sometimes applied to other concepts besides the nonexistence of a local hidden-variable model, such as whether states can be distinguished by local measurements.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Moreover, quantum field theory is often said to be *local* because observables defined within spacetime regions that are spacelike separated must commute.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] These other uses of *local* and *nonlocal* are not discussed further here.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The following subsections use the formalism and theoretical framework developed in the articles bra–ket notation and mathematical formulation of quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Consider two arbitrary quantum systems A and B, with respective Hilbert spaces HA and HB.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] States of the composite system that can be represented in this form are called separable states, or product states.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] However, not all states of the composite system are separable.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] If the composite system is in this state, it is impossible to attribute to either system A or system B a definite pure state.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Another way to say this is that while the von Neumann entropy of the whole state is zero (as it is for any pure state), the entropy of the subsystems is greater than zero.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In this sense, the systems are "entangled".
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The above example is one of four Bell states, which are (maximally) entangled pure states (pure states of the *HA* ⊗ *HB* space, but which cannot be separated into pure states of each HA and HB).
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Now suppose Alice is an observer for system A, and Bob is an observer for system B.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] If in the entangled state given above Alice makes a measurement in the $\{|0\rangle ,|1\rangle \}$ eigenbasis of A, there are two possible outcomes, occurring with equal probability: Alice can obtain the outcome 0, or she can obtain the outcome 1.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] If she obtains the outcome 0, then she can predict with certainty that Bob's result will be 1.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Likewise, if she obtains the outcome 1, then she can predict with certainty that Bob's result will be 0.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In other words, the results of measurements on the two qubits will be perfectly anti-correlated.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] This remains true even if the systems A and B are spatially separated.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] This is the foundation of the EPR paradox.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The outcome of Alice's measurement is random.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Alice cannot decide which state to collapse the composite system into, and therefore cannot transmit information to Bob by acting on her system.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Causality is thus preserved, in this particular scheme.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] For the general argument, see no-communication theorem.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] As mentioned above, a state of a quantum system is given by a unit vector in a Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] More generally, if one has less information about the system, then one calls it an 'ensemble' and describes it by a density matrix, which is a positive-semidefinite matrix, or a trace class when the state space is infinite-dimensional, and which has trace 1.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] where the *w**i* are positive-valued probabilities (they sum up to 1), the vectors *α**i* are unit vectors, and in the infinite-dimensional case, we would take the closure of such states in the trace norm.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] We can interpret ρ as representing an ensemble where $w_{i}$ is the proportion of the ensemble whose states are $|\alpha _{i}\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] When a mixed state has rank 1, it therefore describes a 'pure ensemble'.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] When there is less than total information about the state of a quantum system we need density matrices to represent the state.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Experimentally, a mixed ensemble might be realized as follows.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Consider a "black box" apparatus that spits electrons towards an observer.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The electrons' Hilbert spaces are identical.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The apparatus might produce electrons that are all in the same state; in this case, the electrons received by the observer are then a pure ensemble.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] However, the apparatus could produce electrons in different states.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] For example, it could produce two populations of electrons: one with state $|\mathbf {z} +\rangle$ with spins aligned in the positive **z** direction, and the other with state $|\mathbf {y} -\rangle$ with spins aligned in the negative **y** direction.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Generally, this is a mixed ensemble, as there can be any number of populations, each corresponding to a different state.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Following the definition above, for a bipartite composite system, mixed states are just density matrices on *HA* ⊗ *HB*.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] where the *w**i* are positively valued probabilities, ${\textstyle \sum _{j}|c_{ij}|^{2}=1}$ , and the vectors are unit vectors.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] This is self-adjoint and positive and has trace 1.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] where the *w**i* are positively valued probabilities and the $\rho _{i}^{A}$ s and $\rho _{i}^{B}$ s are themselves mixed states (density operators) on the subsystems A and B respectively.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In other words, a state is separable if it is a probability distribution over uncorrelated states, or product states.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] By writing the density matrices as sums of pure ensembles and expanding, we may assume without loss of generality that $\rho _{i}^{A}$ and $\rho _{i}^{B}$ are themselves pure ensembles.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] A state is then said to be entangled if it is not separable.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In general, finding out whether or not a mixed state is entangled is considered difficult.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The general bipartite case has been shown to be NP-hard.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] For the 2 × 2 and 2 × 3 cases, a necessary and sufficient criterion for separability is given by the famous Positive Partial Transpose (PPT) condition.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The idea of a reduced density matrix was introduced by Paul Dirac in 1930.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Consider as above systems A and B each with a Hilbert space HA, HB.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] As indicated above, in general there is no way to associate a pure state to the component system A.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] However, it still is possible to associate a density matrix.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] which is the projection operator onto this state.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The sum occurs over $N_{B}:=\dim(H_{B})$ and $I_{A}$ the identity operator in $H_{A}$ . ρA is sometimes called the reduced density matrix of ρ on subsystem A.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Colloquially, we "trace out" or "trace over" system B to obtain the reduced density matrix on A.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] This demonstrates that the reduced density matrix for an entangled pure ensemble is a mixed ensemble.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] the projection operator onto $|\psi \rangle _{A}$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In general, a bipartite pure state *ρ* is entangled if and only if its reduced states are mixed rather than pure.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In quantum information theory, entangled states are considered a 'resource', i.e., something costly to produce and that allows implementing valuable transformations.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The setting in which this perspective is most evident is that of "distant labs", i.e., two quantum systems labelled "A" and "B" on each of which arbitrary quantum operations can be performed, but which do not interact with each other quantum mechanically.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The only interaction allowed is the exchange of classical information, which combined with the most general local quantum operations gives rise to the class of operations called LOCC (local operations and classical communication).
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] These operations do not allow the production of entangled states between systems A and B.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] But if A and B are provided with a supply of entangled states, then these, together with LOCC operations can enable a larger class of transformations.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] If Alice and Bob share an entangled state, Alice can tell Bob over a telephone call how to reproduce a quantum state $|\Psi \rangle$ she has in her lab.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Alice performs a joint measurement on $|\Psi \rangle$ together with her half of the entangled state and tells Bob the results.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Using Alice's results Bob operates on his half of the entangled state to make it equal to $|\Psi \rangle$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Since Alice's measurement necessarily erases the quantum state of the system in her lab, the state $|\Psi \rangle$ is not copied, but transferred: it is said to be "teleported" to Bob's laboratory through this protocol.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Entanglement swapping is variant of teleportation that allows two parties that have never interacted to share an entangled state.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The swapping protocol begins with two EPR sources.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] One source emits an entangled pair of particles A and B, while the other emits a second entangled pair of particles C and D.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Particles B and C are subjected to a measurement in the basis of Bell states.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The state of the remaining particles, A and D, collapses to a Bell state, leaving them entangled despite never having interacted with each other.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] An interaction between a qubit of A and a qubit of B can be realized by first teleporting A's qubit to B, then letting it interact with B's qubit (which is now a LOCC operation, since both qubits are in B's lab) and then teleporting the qubit back to A.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Two maximally entangled states of two qubits are used up in this process.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Thus entangled states are a resource that enables the realization of quantum interactions (or of quantum channels) in a setting where only LOCC are available, but they are consumed in the process.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] There are other applications where entanglement can be seen as a resource, e.g., private communication or distinguishing quantum states.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Quantum states describing systems made of more than two pieces can also be entangled.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] This illustrates how multipartite entanglement is a more complicated topic than bipartite entanglement: systems composed of three or more parts can exhibit multiple qualitatively different types of entanglement.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] A single particle cannot be maximally entangled with more than a particle at a time, a property called monogamy.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Not all quantum states are equally valuable as a resource.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] One method to quantify this value is to use an entanglement measure that assigns a numerical value to each quantum state.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] However, it is often interesting to settle for a coarser way to compare quantum states.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] This gives rise to different classification schemes.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Most entanglement classes are defined based on whether states can be converted to other states using LOCC or a subclass of these operations.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The smaller the set of allowed operations, the finer the classification.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In this section, the entropy of a mixed state is discussed as well as how it can be viewed as a measure of quantum entanglement.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] When a pair of particles is described by the spin singlet state discussed above, the von Neumann entropy of either particle is log(2), which can be shown to be the maximum entropy for 2 × 2 mixed states.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Entropy provides one tool that can be used to quantify entanglement, although other entanglement measures exist.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] If the overall system is pure, the entropy of one subsystem can be used to measure its degree of entanglement with the other subsystems.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] For bipartite pure states, the von Neumann entropy of reduced states is the unique measure of entanglement in the sense that it is the only function on the family of states that satisfies certain axioms required of an entanglement measure.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] It is a classical result that the Shannon entropy achieves its maximum at, and only at, the uniform probability distribution {1/*n*, ..., 1/*n*}.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] For mixed states, the reduced von Neumann entropy is not the only reasonable entanglement measure.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Rényi entropy can be used as a measure of entanglement.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Entanglement measures quantify the amount of entanglement in a (often viewed as a bipartite) quantum state.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] As aforementioned, entanglement entropy is the standard measure of entanglement for pure states (but no longer a measure of entanglement for mixed states).
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] For mixed states, there are some entanglement measures in the literature and no single one is standard.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Most (but not all) of these entanglement measures reduce for pure states to entanglement entropy, and are difficult (NP-hard) to compute for mixed states as the dimension of the entangled system grows.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The Reeh–Schlieder theorem of quantum field theory is sometimes interpreted as saying that entanglement is omnipresent in the quantum vacuum.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Entanglement has many applications in quantum information theory.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] With the aid of entanglement, otherwise impossible tasks may be achieved.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Among the best-known applications of entanglement are superdense coding and quantum teleportation.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Most researchers believe that entanglement is necessary to realize quantum computing (although this is disputed by some).
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Entanglement is used in some protocols of quantum cryptography, but to prove the security of quantum key distribution (QKD) under standard assumptions does not require entanglement; however, the *device independent* security of QKD is shown exploiting entanglement between the communication partners.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In August 2014, Brazilian researcher Gabriela Barreto Lemos, from the University of Vienna, and team were able to "take pictures" of objects using photons that had not interacted with the subjects, but were entangled with photons that did interact with such objects.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The idea has been adapted to make infrared images using only standard cameras that are insensitive to infrared.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] There are several canonical entangled states that appear often in theory and experiments.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] These four pure states are all maximally entangled and form an orthonormal basis of the Hilbert space of the two qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] They provide examples of how quantum mechanics can violate Bell-type inequalities.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] which reduces to the Bell state $|\Phi ^{+}\rangle$ for *M* = 2.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The traditional GHZ state was defined for *M* = 3.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] GHZ states are occasionally extended to qudits, i.e., systems of *d* rather than 2 dimensions.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Also for *M* > 2 qubits, there are spin squeezed states, a class of squeezed coherent states satisfying certain restrictions on the uncertainty of spin measurements, which are necessarily entangled.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Spin squeezed states are good candidates for enhancing precision measurements using quantum entanglement.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] This is like the Bell state $|\Psi ^{+}\rangle$ except the basis states $|0\rangle$ and $|1\rangle$ have been replaced with "the *N* photons are in one mode" and "the *N* photons are in the other mode".
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Finally, there also exist twin Fock states for bosonic modes, which can be created by feeding a Fock state into two arms leading to a beam splitter.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] They are the sum of multiple NOON states, and can be used to achieve the Heisenberg limit.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] For the appropriately chosen measures of entanglement, Bell, GHZ, and NOON states are maximally entangled while spin squeezed and twin Fock states are only partially entangled.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Entanglement is usually created by direct interactions between subatomic particles.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] These interactions can take numerous forms.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] One of the most commonly used methods is spontaneous parametric down-conversion to generate a pair of photons entangled in polarization.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Other methods include the use of a fiber coupler to confine and mix photons, photons emitted from decay cascade of the bi-exciton in a quantum dot, or the use of the Hong–Ou–Mandel effect.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Quantum entanglement of a particle and its antiparticle, such as an electron and a positron, can be created by partial overlap of the corresponding quantum wave functions in Hardy's interferometer.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In the earliest tests of Bell's theorem, the entangled particles were generated using atomic cascades.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] It is also possible to create entanglement between quantum systems that never directly interacted, through the use of entanglement swapping.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Two independently prepared, identical particles may also be entangled if their wave functions merely spatially overlap, at least partially.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] A density matrix *ρ* is called separable if it can be written as a convex sum of product states, namely ${\rho =\sum _{j}p_{j}\rho _{j}^{(A)}\otimes \rho _{j}^{(B)}}$ with $0\leq p_{j}\leq 1$ probabilities.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] By definition, a state is entangled if it is not separable.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] For 2-qubit and qubit-qutrit systems (2 × 2 and 2 × 3 respectively) the simple Peres–Horodecki criterion provides both a necessary and a sufficient criterion for separability, and thus—inadvertently—for detecting entanglement.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] However, for the general case, the criterion is merely a necessary one for separability, as the problem becomes NP-hard when generalized.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Other separability criteria include (but not limited to) the range criterion, reduction criterion, and those based on uncertainty relations.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] See Ref. for a review of separability criteria in discrete-variable systems and Ref. for a review on techniques and challenges in experimental entanglement certification in discrete-variable systems.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] A numerical approach to the problem is suggested by Jon Magne Leinaas, Jan Myrheim and Eirik Ovrum in their paper "Geometrical aspects of entanglement".
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Leinaas et al. offer a numerical approach, iteratively refining an estimated separable state towards the target state to be tested, and checking if the target state can indeed be reached.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In continuous variable systems, the Peres–Horodecki criterion also applies.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] It was later found that Simon's condition is also necessary and sufficient for $1\oplus n$ -mode Gaussian states, but no longer sufficient for $2\oplus 2$ -mode Gaussian states.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Simon's condition can be generalized by taking into account the higher order moments of canonical operators or by using entropic measures.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] There is a fundamental conflict, referred to as the problem of time, between the way the concept of *time* is used in quantum mechanics, and the role it plays in general relativity.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In standard quantum theories time acts as an independent background through which states evolve, while general relativity treats time as a dynamical variable which relates directly with matter.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Part of the effort to reconcile these approaches to time results in the Wheeler–DeWitt equation, which predicts the state of the universe is timeless or static, contrary to ordinary experience.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Work started by Don Page and William Wootters suggests that the universe appears to evolve for observers on the inside because of energy entanglement between an evolving system and a clock system, both within the universe.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In this way the overall system can remain timeless while parts experience time via entanglement.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The issue remains an open question closely related to attempts at theories of quantum gravity.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In general relativity, gravity arises from the curvature of spacetime and that curvature derives from the distribution of matter.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] However, matter is governed by quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Integration of these two theories faces many problems.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In an (unrealistic) model space called the anti-de Sitter space, the AdS/CFT correspondence allows a quantum gravitational system to be related to a quantum field theory without gravity.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Using this correspondence, Mark Van Raamsdonk suggested that spacetime arises as an emergent phenomenon of the quantum degrees of freedom that are entangled and live in the boundary of the spacetime.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] A Bell test, also known as *Bell inequality test* or *Bell experiment*, is a real-world physics experiment designed to test the theory of quantum mechanics against the hypothesis of local hidden variables.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] These tests empirically evaluate the implications of Bell's theorem.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] To date, all Bell tests have found that the hypothesis of local hidden variables is inconsistent with the way that physical systems behave.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Many types of Bell tests have been performed in physics laboratories, often with the goal of ameliorating problems of experimental design or set-up that could in principle affect the validity of the findings of earlier Bell tests.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] This is known as "closing loopholes in Bell tests".
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In 2023 the LHC using techniques from quantum tomography measured entanglement at the highest energy so far, a rare intersection between quantum information and high energy physics based on theoretical work first proposed in 2021.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] The spin polarization and correlation of the particles was measured and tested for entanglement with concurrence as well as the Peres–Horodecki criterion and subsequently the effect has been confirmed too in the CMS detector.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] In 2020, researchers reported the quantum entanglement between the motion of a millimetre-sized mechanical oscillator and a disparate distant spin system of a cloud of atoms.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Later work complemented this work by quantum-entangling two mechanical oscillators.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Physicists at Brookhaven National Laboratory demonstrated quantum entanglement within protons, showing quarks and gluons are interdependent rather than isolated particles.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-entanglement] Using high-energy electron-proton collisions, they revealed maximal entanglement, reshaping our understanding of proton structure.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] In quantum computing and specifically the quantum circuit model of computation, a **quantum logic gate** (or simply **quantum gate**) is a basic quantum circuit operating on a small number of qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Quantum logic gates are the building blocks of quantum circuits, like classical logic gates are for conventional digital circuits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] According to quantum mechanics, a quantum system can *only either* evolve unitarily according to the Schrödinger equation, or be measured (sometimes called "Observed").
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Quantum gates describe these unitary transformations, that occur when the system is not being measured.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The expression "quantum gate" appears in relation to quantum processors, and in this context they are the logical operations that the quantum computer at the assembly language-level of abstraction (e.g.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] OpenQASM) can perform on the quantum data (qubits or quantum states) that they process, although they can also be whole algorithms (e.g. the Quantum Fourier transform) – But this is only true if such algorithms contains no measurement operations.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] When the quantum data is measured, it is usually transformed into binary bits, which is then sent to a normal ("classical") computer.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The quantum processor behaves like a co-processor to such classical binary processors.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Unlike many classical logic gates, quantum logic gates are reversible.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] It is possible to perform classical computing using only reversible gates.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] For example, the reversible Toffoli gate can implement all Boolean functions, often at the cost of having to use ancilla bits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The Toffoli gate has a direct quantum equivalent, showing that quantum circuits can perform all operations performed by classical circuits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Quantum gates are unitary operators, and are described as unitary matrices relative to some orthonormal basis.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The current notation for quantum gates was developed by many of the founders of quantum information science including Adriano Barenco, Charles Bennett, Richard Cleve, David P.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] DiVincenzo, Norman Margolus, Peter Shor, Tycho Sleator, John A.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Smolin, and Harald Weinfurter, building on notation introduced by Richard Feynman in 1986.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Quantum logic gates are represented by unitary matrices.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] A gate that acts on n qubits (a register) is represented by a $2^{n}\times 2^{n}$ unitary matrix, and the set of all such gates with the group operation of matrix multiplication is the unitary group U(2*n*).
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The quantum states that the gates act upon are unit vectors in $2^{n}$ complex dimensions, with the complex Euclidean norm (the 2-norm).
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The basis vectors (sometimes called *eigenstates*) are the possible outcomes if the state of the qubits is measured, and a quantum state is a linear combination of these outcomes.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The most common quantum gates operate on vector spaces of one or two qubits, just like the common classical logic gates operate on one or two bits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Even though the quantum logic gates belong to continuous symmetry groups, real hardware is inexact and thus limited in precision.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The application of gates typically introduces errors, and the quantum states' fidelities decrease over time.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] If error correction is used, the usable gates are further restricted to a finite set.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Later in this article, this is ignored as the focus is on the ideal quantum gates' properties.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Quantum states are typically represented by "kets", from a notation known as bra–ket.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Here, $v_{0}$ and $v_{1}$ are the complex probability amplitudes of the qubit.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] These values determine the probability of measuring a 0 or a 1, when measuring the state of the qubit.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The value zero is represented by the ket $|0\rangle ={\begin{bmatrix}1\\0\end{bmatrix}}$ , and the value one is represented by the ket $|1\rangle ={\begin{bmatrix}0\\1\end{bmatrix}}$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The tensor product (or Kronecker product) is used to combine quantum states.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The combined state for a qubit register is the tensor product of the constituent qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The tensor product is denoted by the symbol $\otimes$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The action of the gate on a specific quantum state is found by multiplying the vector $|\psi _{1}\rangle$ , which represents the state by the matrix U representing the gate.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] That is, a quantum gate is how a quantum system that is not observed evolves over some specific time, or equivalently, a gate is the unitary time evolution operator U acting on a quantum state for a specific duration.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] There exists an uncountably infinite number of gates.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Some of them have been named by various authors, and below follow some of those most often used in the literature.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] where *I* is basis independent and does not modify the quantum state.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The identity gate is most useful when describing mathematically the result of various gate operations or when discussing multi-qubit circuits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The Pauli gates $(X,Y,Z)$ are the three Pauli matrices $(\sigma _{x},\sigma _{y},\sigma _{z})$ and act on a single qubit.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The Pauli *X*, *Y* and *Z* equate, respectively, to a rotation around the *x*, *y* and *z* axes of the Bloch sphere by $\pi$ radians.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The Pauli-*X* gate is the quantum equivalent of the NOT gate for classical computers with respect to the standard basis $|0\rangle$ , $|1\rangle$ , which distinguishes the *z* axis on the Bloch sphere.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] It is sometimes called a bit-flip as it maps $|0\rangle$ to $|1\rangle$ and $|1\rangle$ to $|0\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Pauli *Z* leaves the basis state $|0\rangle$ unchanged and maps $|1\rangle$ to $-|1\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Due to this nature, Pauli *Z* is sometimes called phase-flip.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The Pauli matrices are involutory, meaning that the square of a Pauli matrix is the identity matrix.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Controlled gates act on 2 or more qubits, where one or more qubits act as a control for some operation.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] For example, the controlled NOT gate (or CNOT or CX) acts on 2 qubits, and performs the NOT operation on the second qubit only when the first qubit is $|1\rangle$ , and otherwise leaves it unchanged.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The CNOT (or controlled Pauli-*X*) gate can be described as the gate that maps the basis states $|a,b\rangle \mapsto |a,a\oplus b\rangle$ , where $\oplus$ is XOR.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Being a Hermitian unitary operator, CNOT has the property that $e^{i\theta U}=(\cos \theta )I+(i\sin \theta )U$ and $U=e^{i{\frac {\pi }{2}}(I-U)}=e^{-i{\frac {\pi }{2}}(I-U)}$ , and is involutory.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] then the *controlled-U gate* is a gate that operates on two qubits in such a way that the first qubit serves as a control.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Circuit diagrams of controlled Pauli gates (from left to right): CNOT (or controlled-X), controlled-Y and controlled-Z.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] When *U* is one of the Pauli operators, *X*,*Y*, *Z*, the respective terms "controlled-*X*", "controlled-*Y*", or "controlled-*Z*" are sometimes used.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Sometimes this is shortened to just C*X*, C*Y* and C*Z*.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Control can be extended to gates with arbitrary number of qubits and functions in programming languages.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Functions can be conditioned on superposition states.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Gates can also be controlled by classical logic.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] A quantum computer is controlled by a classical computer, and behaves like a coprocessor that receives instructions from the classical computer about what gates to execute on which qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Classical control is simply the inclusion, or omission, of gates in the instruction sequence for the quantum computer.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Performing measurements in the middle of a quantum circuit, as opposed to the end of it, is difficult and technically challanging because of timing issues and decoherence.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Because of this, not all quantum computers support these classical if-statement, where quantum data is converted to bits, which then controls the program flow.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The phase shift is a family of single-qubit gates that map the basis states $|0\rangle \mapsto |0\rangle$ and $|1\rangle \mapsto e^{i\varphi }|1\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The probability of measuring a $|0\rangle$ or $|1\rangle$ is unchanged after applying this gate, however it modifies the phase of the quantum state.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] This is equivalent to tracing a horizontal circle (a line of constant latitude), or a rotation about the z-axis on the Bloch sphere by $\varphi$ radians.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] where $\varphi$ is the *phase shift* with the period 2π.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Note that the phase gate $P(\varphi )$ is not Hermitian (except for all $\varphi =n\pi ,n\in \mathbb {Z}$ ).
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] These gates are different from their Hermitian conjugates: $P^{\dagger }(\varphi )=P(-\varphi )$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The two adjoint (or conjugate transpose) gates $S^{\dagger }$ and $T^{\dagger }$ are sometimes included in instruction sets.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The Hadamard or Walsh-Hadamard gate, named after Jacques Hadamard (French: [adamaʁ]) and Joseph L.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] It maps the basis states ${\textstyle |0\rangle \mapsto {\frac {|0\rangle +|1\rangle }{\sqrt {2}}}}$ and ${\textstyle |1\rangle \mapsto {\frac {|0\rangle -|1\rangle }{\sqrt {2}}}}$ (it creates an equal superposition state if given a computational basis state).
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The Hadamard gate performs a rotation of $\pi$ about the axis $({\hat {x}}+{\hat {z}})/{\sqrt {2}}$ at the Bloch sphere, and is therefore involutory.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] If the Hermitian (so $H^{\dagger }=H^{-1}=H$ ) Hadamard gate is used to perform a change of basis, it flips ${\hat {x}}$ and ${\hat {z}}$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The Toffoli gate, named after Tommaso Toffoli and also called the CCNOT gate or Deutsch gate $D(\pi /2)$ , is a 3-bit gate that is universal for classical computation but not for quantum computation.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The quantum Toffoli gate is the same gate, defined for 3 qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] If we limit ourselves to only accepting input qubits that are $|0\rangle$ and $|1\rangle$ , then if the first two bits are in the state $|1\rangle$ it applies a Pauli-*X* (or NOT) on the third bit, else it does nothing.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] It is an example of a CC-U (controlled-controlled Unitary) gate.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Since it is the quantum analog of a classical gate, it is completely specified by its truth table.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The Toffoli gate is universal when combined with the single qubit Hadamard gate.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The Toffoli gate is related to the classical AND ( $\land$ ) and XOR ( $\oplus$ ) operations as it performs the mapping $|a,b,c\rangle \mapsto |a,b,c\oplus (a\land b)\rangle$ on states in the computational basis.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] A set of **universal quantum gates** is any set of gates to which any operation possible on a quantum computer can be reduced, that is, any other unitary operation can be expressed as a finite sequence of gates from the set.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Technically, this is impossible with anything less than an uncountable set of gates since the number of possible quantum gates is uncountable, whereas the number of finite sequences from a finite set is countable.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] To solve this problem, we only require that any quantum operation can be approximated by a sequence of gates from this finite set.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Moreover, for unitaries on a constant number of qubits, the Solovay–Kitaev theorem guarantees that this can be done efficiently.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Checking if a set of quantum gates is universal can be done using group theory methods and/or relation to (approximate) unitary t-designs.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The spectral gap conjecture, if true, would imply that a generically chosen set of quantum gates is efficiently universal.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] A single-gate set of universal quantum gates can also be formulated using the parametrized three-qubit Deutsch gate $D(\theta )$ , named after physicist David Deutsch.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Unfortunately, a working Deutsch gate has remained out of reach, due to lack of a protocol.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] There are some proposals to realize a Deutsch gate with dipole–dipole interaction in neutral atoms.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] A universal logic gate for reversible classical computing, the Toffoli gate, is reducible to the Deutsch gate $D(\pi /2)$ , thus showing that all reversible classical logic operations can be performed on a universal quantum computer.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] There also exist single two-qubit gates sufficient for universality.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] In 1996, Adriano Barenco showed that the Deutsch gate can be decomposed using only a single two-qubit gate (Barenco gate), but it is hard to realize experimentally.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] This feature is exclusive to quantum circuits, as there is no classical two-bit gate that is both reversible and universal.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Universal two-qubit gates could be implemented to improve classical reversible circuits in fast low-power microprocessors.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Assume that we have two gates *A* and *B* that both act on n qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] When *B* is put after *A* in a series circuit, then the effect of the two gates can be described as a single gate *C*.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The resulting gate *C* will have the same dimensions as *A* and *B*.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The order in which the gates would appear in a circuit diagram is reversed when multiplying them together.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The product symbol ( $\cdot$ ) is often omitted.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] All real exponents of unitary matrices are also unitary matrices, and all quantum gates are unitary matrices.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Positive integer exponents are equivalent to sequences of serially wired gates (e.g. $X^{3}=X\cdot X\cdot X$ ), and the real exponents is a generalization of the series circuit.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] For example, $X^{\pi }$ and ${\sqrt {X}}=X^{1/2}$ are both valid quantum gates.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The identity matrix ( I ) behaves like a NOP and can be represented as bare wire in quantum circuits, or not shown at all.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] All gates are unitary matrices, so that $U^{\dagger }U=UU^{\dagger }=I$ and $U^{\dagger }=U^{-1}$ , where $\dagger$ is the conjugate transpose.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] This means that negative exponents of gates are unitary inverses of their positively exponentiated counterparts: $U^{-n}=(U^{n})^{\dagger }$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] For example, some negative exponents of the phase shift gates are $T^{-1}=T^{\dagger }$ and $T^{-2}=(T^{2})^{\dagger }=S^{\dagger }$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Note that for a Hermitian matrix $H^{\dagger }=H,$ and because of unitarity, $HH^{\dagger }=I,$ so $H^{2}=I$ for all Hermitian gates.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Examples of Hermitian gates are the Pauli gates, Hadamard, CNOT, SWAP and Toffoli.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The exponent of a gate is a multiple of the duration of time that the time evolution operator is applied to a quantum state.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] E.g., in a spin qubit quantum computer the ${\sqrt {\mathrm {SWAP} }}$ gate could be realized via exchange interaction on the spin of two electrons for half the duration of a full exchange interaction.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The tensor product (or Kronecker product) of two quantum gates is the gate that is equal to the two gates in parallel.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Both the Pauli-*X* and the Pauli-*Y* gate act on a single qubit.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Sometimes the tensor product symbol is omitted, and indexes are used for the operators instead.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The gate $H_{2}=H\otimes H$ is the Hadamard gate ( H ) applied in parallel on 2 qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] This "two-qubit parallel Hadamard gate" will, when applied to, for example, the two-qubit zero-vector ( $|00\rangle$ ), create a quantum state that has equal probability of being observed in any of its four possible outcomes; $|00\rangle$ , $|01\rangle$ , $|10\rangle$ , and $|11\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Here the amplitude for each measurable state is 1⁄2.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The probability to observe any state is the square of the absolute value of the measurable states amplitude, which in the above example means that there is one in four that we observe any one of the individual four cases.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] $H_{2}$ performs the Hadamard transform on two qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Similarly the gate $\underbrace {H\otimes H\otimes \dots \otimes H} _{n{\text{ times}}}=\bigotimes _{i=0}^{n-1}H=H^{\otimes n}=H_{n}$ performs a Hadamard transform on a register of n qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] This state is a *uniform superposition* and it is generated as the first step in some search algorithms, for example in amplitude amplification and phase estimation.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Measuring this state results in a random number between $|0\rangle$ and $|2^{n}-1\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] How random the number is depends on the fidelity of the logic gates.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] If not measured, it is a quantum state with equal probability amplitude ${\frac {1}{\sqrt {2^{n}}}}$ for each of its possible states.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] If two or more qubits are viewed as a single quantum state, this combined state is equal to the tensor product of the constituent qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Any state that can be written as a tensor product from the constituent subsystems are called *separable states*.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] On the other hand, an *entangled state* is any state that cannot be tensor-factorized, or in other words: *An entangled state can not be written as a tensor product of its constituent qubits states.* Special care must be taken when applying gates to constituent qubits that make up entangled states.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] If we have a set of *N* qubits that are entangled and wish to apply a quantum gate on *M* < *N* qubits in the set, we will have to extend the gate to take *N* qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] This application can be done by combining the gate with an identity matrix such that their tensor product becomes a gate that act on *N* qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The identity matrix ( I ) is a representation of the gate that maps every state to itself (i.e., does nothing at all).
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] In a circuit diagram the identity gate or matrix will often appear as just a bare wire.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] For example, the Hadamard gate ( H ) acts on a single qubit, but if we feed it the first of the two qubits that constitute the entangled Bell state ${\frac {|00\rangle +|11\rangle }{\sqrt {2}}}$ , we cannot write that operation easily.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The gate K can now be applied to any two-qubit state, entangled or otherwise.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The gate K will leave the second qubit untouched and apply the Hadamard transform to the first qubit.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The time complexity for multiplying two $n\times n$ -matrices is at least $\Omega (n^{2}\log n)$ , if using a classical machine.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Because the size of a gate that operates on q qubits is $2^{q}\times 2^{q}$ it means that the time for simulating a step in a quantum circuit (by means of multiplying the gates) that operates on generic entangled states is $\Omega ({2^{q}}^{2}\log({2^{q}}))$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] For this reason it is believed to be intractable to simulate large entangled quantum systems using classical computers.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Subsets of the gates, such as the Clifford gates, or the trivial case of circuits that only implement classical Boolean functions (e.g. combinations of X, CNOT, Toffoli), can however be efficiently simulated on classical computers.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The state vector of a quantum register with n qubits is $2^{n}$ complex entries.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Storing the probability amplitudes as a list of floating point values is not tractable for large n .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Because all quantum logical gates are reversible, any composition of multiple gates is also reversible.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] All products and tensor products (i.e. series and parallel combinations) of unitary matrices are also unitary matrices.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] This means that it is possible to construct an inverse of all algorithms and functions, as long as they contain only gates.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Initialization, measurement, I/O and spontaneous decoherence are side effects in quantum computers.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Gates however are purely functional and bijective.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The dagger ( $\dagger$ ) denotes the conjugate transpose.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] It is also called the Hermitian adjoint.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Similarly if the function G consists of two gates A and B in parallel, then $G=A\otimes B$ and $G^{\dagger }=(A\otimes B)^{\dagger }=A^{\dagger }\otimes B^{\dagger }$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Gates that are their own unitary inverses are called Hermitian or self-adjoint operators.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Some elementary gates such as the Hadamard (*H*) and the Pauli gates (*I*, *X*, *Y*, *Z*) are Hermitian operators, while others like the phase shift (*S*, *T*, *P*, CPhase) gates generally are not.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] For example, an algorithm for addition can be used for subtraction, if it is being "run in reverse", as its unitary inverse.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The inverse quantum Fourier transform is the unitary inverse.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Unitary inverses can also be used for uncomputation.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Programming languages for quantum computers, such as Microsoft's Q#, Bernhard Ömer's QCL, and IBM's Qiskit, contain function inversion as programming concepts.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Measurement (sometimes called *observation*) is irreversible and therefore not a quantum gate, because it assigns the observed quantum state to a single value.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Measurement takes a quantum state and projects it to one of the basis vectors, with a likelihood equal to the square of the vector's length (in the 2-norm) along that basis vector.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] This is known as the Born rule and appears as a stochastic non-reversible operation as it probabilistically sets the quantum state equal to the basis vector that represents the measured state.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] At the instant of measurement, the state is said to "collapse" to the definite single value that was measured.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Why and how, or even if the quantum state collapses at measurement, is called the measurement problem.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The probability of measuring a value with probability amplitude $\phi$ is $1\geq |\phi |^{2}\geq 0$ , where $|\cdot |$ is the modulus.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Measuring a single qubit, whose quantum state is represented by the vector $a|0\rangle +b|1\rangle ={\begin{bmatrix}a\\b\end{bmatrix}}$ , will result in $|0\rangle$ with probability $|a|^{2}$ , and in $|1\rangle$ with probability $|b|^{2}$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] For example, measuring a qubit with the quantum state ${\frac {|0\rangle -i|1\rangle }{\sqrt {2}}}={\frac {1}{\sqrt {2}}}{\begin{bmatrix}1\\-i\end{bmatrix}}$ will yield with equal probability either $|0\rangle$ or $|1\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] A quantum state $|\Psi \rangle$ that spans n qubits can be written as a vector in $2^{n}$ complex dimensions: $|\Psi \rangle \in \mathbb {C} ^{2^{n}}$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] This is because the tensor product of n qubits is a vector in $2^{n}$ dimensions.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] This way, a register of n qubits can be measured to $2^{n}$ distinct states, similar to how a register of n classical bits can hold $2^{n}$ distinct states.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Unlike with the bits of classical computers, quantum states can have non-zero probability amplitudes in multiple measurable values simultaneously.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The sum of all probabilities for all outcomes must always be equal to 1.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Another way to say this is that the Pythagorean theorem generalized to $\mathbb {C} ^{2^{n}}$ has that all quantum states $|\Psi \rangle$ with n qubits must satisfy ${\textstyle 1=\sum _{x=0}^{2^{n}-1}|a_{x}|^{2},}$ where $a_{x}$ is the probability amplitude for measurable state $|x\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] A geometric interpretation of this is that the possible value-space of a quantum state $|\Psi \rangle$ with n qubits is the surface of the unit sphere in $\mathbb {C} ^{2^{n}}$ and that the unitary transforms (i.e. quantum logic gates) applied to it are rotations on the sphere.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The rotations that the gates perform form the symmetry group U(2n).
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Measurement is then a probabilistic projection of the points at the surface of this complex sphere onto the basis vectors that span the space (and labels the outcomes).
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] In many cases the space is represented as a Hilbert space ${\mathcal {H}}$ rather than some specific $2^{n}$ -dimensional complex space.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The number of dimensions (defined by the basis vectors, and thus also the possible outcomes from measurement) is then often implied by the operands, for example as the required state space for solving a problem.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] In Grover's algorithm, Grover named this generic basis vector set *"the database"*.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The selection of basis vectors against which to measure a quantum state will influence the outcome of the measurement.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] See change of basis and Von Neumann entropy for details.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] In quantum mechanics, the basis vectors constitute an orthonormal basis.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] An example of usage of an alternative measurement basis is in the BB84 cipher.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] If two quantum states (i.e. qubits, or registers) are entangled (meaning that their combined state cannot be expressed as a tensor product), measurement of one register affects or reveals the state of the other register by partially or entirely collapsing its state too.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] This effect can be used for computation, and is used in many algorithms.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] It cannot be described as a tensor product of two qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] because for example w needs to be both non-zero and zero in the case of xw and yw.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The quantum state *spans* the two qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Measuring one of the two qubits that make up this Bell state will result in that the other qubit logically must have the same value, both must be the same: Either it will be found in the state $|00\rangle$ , or in the state $|11\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] If we measure one of the qubits to be for example $|1\rangle$ , then the other qubit must also be $|1\rangle$ , because their combined state *became* $|11\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Measurement of one of the qubits collapses the entire quantum state, that span the two qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The GHZ state is a similar entangled quantum state that spans three or more qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] This type of value-assignment occurs *instantaneously over any distance* and this has as of 2018 been experimentally verified by QUESS for distances of up to 1200 kilometers.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] That the phenomena appears to happen instantaneously as opposed to the time it would take to traverse the distance separating the qubits at the speed of light is called the EPR paradox, and it is an open question in physics how to resolve this.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Originally it was solved by giving up the assumption of local realism, but other interpretations have also emerged.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] For more information see the Bell test experiments.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The no-communication theorem proves that this phenomenon cannot be used for faster-than-light communication of classical information.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Take a register A with n qubits all initialized to $|0\rangle$ , and feed it through a parallel Hadamard gate ${\textstyle H^{\otimes n}}$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Register A will then enter the state ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{\sqrt {2^{n}}}}\sum _{k=0}^{2^{n}-1}|k\rangle }$ that have equal probability of when measured to be in any of its $2^{n}$ possible states; $|0\rangle$ to $|2^{n}-1\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Take a second register B, also with n qubits initialized to $|0\rangle$ and pairwise CNOT its qubits with the qubits in register A, such that for each p the qubits $A_{p}$ and $B_{p}$ forms the state $|A_{p}B_{p}\rangle ={\frac {|00\rangle +|11\rangle }{\sqrt {2}}}$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] If we now measure the qubits in register A, then register B will be found to contain the same value as A.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] If we however instead apply a quantum logic gate F on A and then measure, then $|A\rangle =F|B\rangle \iff F^{\dagger }|A\rangle =|B\rangle$ , where $F^{\dagger }$ is the unitary inverse of F.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Because of how unitary inverses of gates act, $F^{\dagger }|A\rangle =F^{-1}(|A\rangle )=|B\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The equality will hold no matter in which order measurement is performed (on the registers A or B), assuming that F has run to completion.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Measurement can even be randomly and concurrently interleaved qubit by qubit, since the measurements assignment of one qubit will limit the possible value-space from the other entangled qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Even though the equalities holds, the probabilities for measuring the possible outcomes may change as a result of applying F, as may be the intent in a quantum search algorithm.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] This effect of value-sharing via entanglement is used in Shor's algorithm, phase estimation and in quantum counting.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Using the Fourier transform to amplify the probability amplitudes of the solution states for some problem is a generic method known as "Fourier fishing".
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Functions and routines that only use gates can themselves be described as matrices, just like the smaller gates.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The matrix that represents a quantum function acting on q qubits has size $2^{q}\times 2^{q}$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] For example, a function that acts on a "qubyte" (a register of 8 qubits) would be represented by a matrix with $2^{8}\times 2^{8}=256\times 256$ elements.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Unitary transformations that are not in the set of gates natively available at the quantum computer (the primitive gates) can be synthesised, or approximated, by combining the available primitive gates in a circuit.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] One way to do this is to factor the matrix that encodes the unitary transformation into a product of tensor products (i.e. series and parallel circuits) of the available primitive gates.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The group U(2*q*) is the symmetry group for the gates that act on q qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Factorization is then the problem of finding a path in U(2*q*) from the generating set of primitive gates.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The Solovay–Kitaev theorem shows that given a sufficient set of primitive gates, there exist an efficient approximate for any gate.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] For the general case with a large number of qubits this direct approach to circuit synthesis is intractable.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] This puts a limit on how large functions can be brute-force factorized into primitive quantum gates.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Typically quantum programs are instead built using relatively small and simple quantum functions, similar to normal classical programming.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Because of the gates unitary nature, all functions must be reversible and always be bijective mappings of input to output.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] There must always exist a function $F^{-1}$ such that $F^{-1}(F(|\psi \rangle ))=|\psi \rangle$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Functions that are not invertible can be made invertible by adding ancilla qubits to the input or the output, or both.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] After the function has run to completion, the ancilla qubits can then either be uncomputed or left untouched.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Measuring or otherwise collapsing the quantum state of an ancilla qubit (e.g. by re-initializing the value of it, or by its spontaneous decoherence) that have not been uncomputed may result in errors, as their state may be entangled with the qubits that are still being used in computations.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] In our example, this can be done by passing on one of the input registers to the output: $F(|a\rangle \otimes |b\rangle )=|a+b{\pmod {2^{n}}}\rangle \otimes |a\rangle$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The output can then be used to compute the input (i.e. given the output $a+b$ and a , we can easily find the input; a is given and $(a+b)-a=b$ ) and the function is made bijective.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] All Boolean algebraic expressions can be encoded as unitary transforms (quantum logic gates), for example by using combinations of the Pauli-X, CNOT and Toffoli gates.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] These gates are functionally complete in the Boolean logic domain.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] There are many unitary transforms available in the libraries of Q#, QCL, Qiskit, and other quantum programming languages.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] In QCL, decrement is done by "undoing" increment.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The prefix `!` is used to instead run the unitary inverse of the function.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] The `cond` keyword means that the function can be conditional.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Measurement of quantum registers results in binary values that the classical computer can use in its computations.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Quantum algorithms often contain both a classical and a quantum part.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Unmeasured I/O (sending qubits to remote computers without collapsing their quantum states) can be used to create networks of quantum computers.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Entanglement swapping can then be used to realize distributed algorithms with quantum computers that are not directly connected.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-logic-gate] Examples of distributed algorithms that only require the use of a handful of quantum logic gates are superdense coding, the quantum Byzantine agreement and the BB84 cipherkey exchange protocol.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] An example is a qubit used in quantum information processing.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] where $|\Psi \rangle$ is the quantum state of the qubit, and $|0\rangle$ , $|1\rangle$ denote particular solutions to the Schrödinger equation in Dirac notation weighted by the two probability amplitudes $c_{0}$ and $c_{1}$ that both are complex numbers.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] Here $|0\rangle$ corresponds to the classical 0 bit, and $|1\rangle$ to the classical 1 bit.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] The probabilities of measuring the system in the $|0\rangle$ or $|1\rangle$ state are given by $|c_{0}|^{2}$ and $|c_{1}|^{2}$ respectively (see the Born rule).
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] Before the measurement occurs the qubit is in a superposition of both states.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] The interference fringes in the double-slit experiment provide another example of the superposition principle.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] The theory of quantum mechanics postulates that a wave equation completely describes the state of a quantum system at all times.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] Furthermore, this differential equation is restricted to be linear and homogeneous.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] These conditions mean that for any two solutions of the wave equation, $\Psi _{1}$ and $\Psi _{2}$ , a linear combination of those solutions also solve the wave equation: $\Psi =c_{1}\Psi _{1}+c_{2}\Psi _{2}$ for arbitrary complex coefficients $c_{1}$ and $c_{2}$ .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] If the wave equation has more than two solutions, combinations of all such solutions are again valid solutions.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] This transformation is itself a quantum superposition and every position wave function can be represented as a superposition of momentum wave functions and vice versa.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] These superpositions involve an infinite number of component waves.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] Other transformations express a quantum solution as a superposition of eigenvectors, each corresponding to a possible result of a measurement on the quantum system.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] An eigenvector $\psi _{i}$ for a mathematical operator, ${\hat {A}}$ , has the equation ${\hat {A}}\psi _{i}=\lambda _{i}\psi _{i}$ where $\lambda _{i}$ is one possible measured quantum value for the observable A .
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] A superposition of these eigenvectors can represent any solution: $\Psi =\sum _{n}a_{i}\psi _{i}.$ The states like $\psi _{i}$ are called basis states.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] Important mathematical operations on quantum system solutions can be performed using only the coefficients of the superposition, suppressing the details of the superposed functions.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] This leads to quantum systems expressed in the Dirac bra-ket notation: $|v\rangle =d_{1}|1\rangle +d_{2}|2\rangle$ This approach is especially effective for systems like quantum spin with no classical coordinate analog.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] Such shorthand notation is very common in textbooks and papers on quantum mechanics, and superposition of basis states is a fundamental tool in quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] where $|n\rangle$ are the energy eigenstates of the Hamiltonian.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] where $\phi _{\alpha }(x)=\langle x|\alpha \rangle$ is the projection of the state into the $|x\rangle$ basis and is called the wave function of the particle.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] In both instances we notice that $|\alpha \rangle$ can be expanded as a superposition of an infinite number of basis states.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] is a solution of the Schrödinger equation but is not generally an eigenstate because $E_{n}$ and $E_{n'}$ are not generally equal.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] We say that $|\Psi \rangle$ is made up of a superposition of energy eigenstates.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] Now consider the more concrete case of an electron that has either spin up or down.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] where $|{\uparrow }\rangle$ and $|{\downarrow }\rangle$ denote spin-up and spin-down states respectively.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] where the probability of finding the particle with either spin up or down is normalized to 1.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] where we have a general state $\Psi$ is the sum of the tensor products of the position space wave functions and spinors.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] Successful experiments involving superpositions of relatively large (by the standards of quantum physics) objects have been performed.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] In quantum computers, a qubit is the analog of the classical information bit, but rather than having one of two distinct values, qubits are a superposition of two values.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] Controlling this superposition qubits is a central challenge in quantum computation.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] The superposition needs to be robust to unintended interactions and yet interactions are needed for computing with qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/quantum-superposition] Qubit systems like nuclear spins with small coupling strength are robust to outside disturbances but the same small coupling makes it difficult to readout results.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] In quantum computing, a **qubit** (/ˈkjuːbɪt/) or **quantum bit** is a basic unit of quantum information, the quantum version of the classic binary bit.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] A qubit can be physically realized with a two-state (or two-level) quantum-mechanical system, one of the simplest quantum systems displaying the peculiarity of quantum mechanics.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Examples include the spin of the electron in which the two levels can be taken as spin up and spin down; or the polarization of a single photon in which the two spin states (left-handed and the right-handed circular polarization) can also be measured as horizontal and vertical linear polarization.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] In a classical system, a bit would have to be in one state or the other.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] However, quantum mechanics allows the qubit to be in a coherent superposition of multiple states simultaneously, a property that is fundamental to quantum mechanics and quantum computing.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] A qubit can be generalized as a d=2 qudit or a binary *qudit*.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] The coining of the term *qubit* is attributed to Benjamin Schumacher.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] In the acknowledgments of his 1995 paper, Schumacher states that the term *qubit* was created in jest during a conversation with William Wootters.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] A binary digit, characterized as 0 or 1, is used to represent information in classical computers.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] When averaged over both of its states (0,1), a binary digit can represent up to one bit of information content, where a bit is the basic unit of information.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] However, in this article, the word bit is synonymous with a binary digit.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] There are two possible outcomes for the measurement of a qubit, usually taken to have the values "0" and "1", like a bit.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] However, whereas the state of a bit can only be binary (either 0 or 1), the general state of a qubit according to quantum mechanics can be an arbitrary coherent superposition of *all* computable states simultaneously.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Moreover, whereas a measurement of a classical bit would not disturb its state, a measurement of a qubit would destroy its coherence and irrevocably disturb the superposition state.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] It is possible to fully encode one bit in one qubit.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] However, a qubit can hold more information, e.g., up to two bits using superdense coding (see Holevo's theorem).
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] A bit is always completely in either one of its two states, and a set of n bits (e.g. a processor register or some bit array) can only hold a single of its 2n possible states at any time.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] A quantum state can be in a superposition state, which means that the qubit can have non-zero probability amplitude in both its states simultaneously (popularly expressed as "it can be in both states simultaneously").
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Furthermore, a set of n bits can be represented by n binary digits, simply by concatenating the representations of each of the bits, whereas a set of n qubits, which is also called a register, requires 2n complex numbers to describe its superposition state vector.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] In quantum mechanics, the general quantum state of a qubit can be represented by a linear superposition of its two orthonormal basis states (or basis vectors).
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] These vectors are usually denoted as $|0\rangle ={\bigl [}{\begin{smallmatrix}1\\0\end{smallmatrix}}{\bigr ]}$ and $|1\rangle ={\bigl [}{\begin{smallmatrix}0\\1\end{smallmatrix}}{\bigr ]}$ .
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] They are written in the conventional Dirac—or "bra–ket"—notation; the $|0\rangle$ and $|1\rangle$ are pronounced "ket 0" and "ket 1", respectively.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] These two orthonormal basis states, $\{|0\rangle ,|1\rangle \}$ , together called the computational basis, are said to span the two-dimensional linear vector (Hilbert) space of the qubit.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Qubit basis states can also be combined to form product basis states.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] A set of qubits taken together is called a quantum register.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] In general, *n* qubits are represented by a superposition state vector in 2*n* dimensional Hilbert space.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] A pure qubit state is a coherent superposition of the basis states.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] where *α* and *β* are the probability amplitudes, and are both complex numbers.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] When we measure this qubit in the standard basis, according to the Born rule, the probability of outcome ${|0\rangle }$ with value "0" is ${|\alpha |}^{2}$ and the probability of outcome ${|1\rangle }$ with value "1" is ${|\beta |}^{2}$ .
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] The probability amplitudes, $\alpha$ and $\beta$ , encode more than just the probabilities of the outcomes of a measurement; the *relative phase* between $\alpha$ and $\beta$ is, for example, responsible for quantum interference, as seen in the double-slit experiment.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] It might, at first sight, seem that there should be four degrees of freedom in ${|\psi \rangle }=\alpha {|0\rangle }+\beta {|1\rangle }\,$ , as $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are complex numbers with two degrees of freedom each.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] However, one degree of freedom is removed by the normalization constraint |*α*|2 + |*β*|2 = 1.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] This means, with a suitable change of coordinates, one can eliminate one of the degrees of freedom.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] where $e^{i\varphi }$ is the physically significant *relative phase*.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] The possible quantum states for a single qubit can be visualised using a Bloch sphere (see picture).
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Represented on such a 2-sphere, a classical bit could only be at the "North Pole" or the "South Pole", in the locations where ${|0\rangle }$ and ${|1\rangle }$ are respectively.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] This particular choice of the polar axis is arbitrary, however.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] The rest of the surface of the Bloch sphere is inaccessible to a classical bit, but a pure qubit state can be represented by any point on the surface.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] For example, the pure qubit state $({|0\rangle }+{|1\rangle })/{\sqrt {2}}$ would lie on the equator of the sphere at the positive X-axis.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] In the classical limit, a qubit, which can have quantum states anywhere on the Bloch sphere, reduces to the classical bit, which can be found only at either poles.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] The surface of the Bloch sphere is a two-dimensional space, which represents the observable state space of the pure qubit states.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] This state space has two local degrees of freedom, which can be represented by the two angles $\varphi$ and $\theta$ .
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] A pure state is fully specified by a single ket, ${|\psi \rangle }=\alpha {|0\rangle }+\beta {|1\rangle },\,$ a coherent superposition, represented by a point on the surface of the Bloch sphere as described above.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Coherence is essential for a qubit to be in a superposition state.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] With interactions, quantum noise and decoherence, it is possible to put the qubit in a mixed state, a statistical combination or "incoherent mixture" of different pure states.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Mixed states can be represented by points *inside* the Bloch sphere (or in the Bloch ball).
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] A mixed qubit state has three degrees of freedom: the angles $\varphi$ and $\theta$ , as well as the length r of the vector that represents the mixed state.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Quantum error correction can be used to maintain the purity of qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Various kinds of physical operations can be performed on qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] An important distinguishing feature between qubits and classical bits is that multiple qubits can exhibit quantum entanglement; the qubit itself is an exhibition of quantum entanglement.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] In this case, quantum entanglement is a local or nonlocal property of two or more qubits that allows a set of qubits to express higher correlation than is possible in classical systems.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] The simplest system to display quantum entanglement is the system of two qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] In this state, called an *equal superposition*, there are equal probabilities of measuring either product state ${|00\rangle }$ or ${|11\rangle }$ , as ${|1/{\sqrt {2}}|}^{2}=1/2$ .
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] In other words, there is no way to tell if the first qubit has value "0" or "1" and likewise for the second qubit.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Imagine that these two entangled qubits are separated, with one each given to Alice and Bob.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Alice makes a measurement of her qubit, obtaining—with equal probabilities—either ${|0\rangle }$ or ${|1\rangle }$ , i.e., she can now tell if her qubit has value "0" or "1".
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Because of the qubits' entanglement, Bob must now get exactly the same measurement as Alice.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] For example, if she measures a ${|0\rangle }$ , Bob must measure the same, as ${|00\rangle }$ is the only state where Alice's qubit is a ${|0\rangle }$ .
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] In short, for these two entangled qubits, whatever Alice measures, so would Bob, with perfect correlation, in any basis, however far apart they may be and even though both can not tell if their qubit has value "0" or "1"—a most surprising circumstance that cannot be explained by classical physics.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Controlled gates act on 2 or more qubits, where one or more qubits act as a control for some specified operation.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] In particular, the controlled NOT gate (CNOT or CX) acts on 2 qubits, and performs the NOT operation on the second qubit only when the first qubit is ${|1\rangle }$ , and otherwise leaves it unchanged.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] A common application of the CNOT gate is to maximally entangle two qubits into the ${|\Phi ^{+}\rangle }$ Bell state.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] The ${|\Phi ^{+}\rangle }$ Bell state forms part of the setup of the superdense coding, quantum teleportation, and entangled quantum cryptography algorithms.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Quantum entanglement also allows multiple states (such as the Bell state mentioned above) to be acted on simultaneously, unlike classical bits that can only have one value at a time.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Entanglement is a necessary ingredient of any quantum computation that cannot be done efficiently on a classical computer.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Many of the successes of quantum computation and communication, such as quantum teleportation and superdense coding, make use of entanglement, suggesting that entanglement is a resource that is unique to quantum computation.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] A major hurdle facing quantum computing, as of 2018, in its quest to surpass classical digital computing, is noise in quantum gates that limits the size of quantum circuits that can be executed reliably.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] A number of qubits taken together is a qubit register.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Quantum computers perform calculations by manipulating qubits within a register.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] The term **qudit** denotes the unit of quantum information that can be realized in suitable *d*-level quantum systems.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Qudits are similar to the integer types in classical computing, and may be mapped to (or realized by) arrays of qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Qudits where the *d*-level system is not an exponent of 2 cannot be mapped to arrays of qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] It is for example possible to have 5-level qudits.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] In 2017, scientists at the National Institute of Scientific Research constructed a pair of qudits with 10 different states each, giving more computational power than 6 qubits.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] In 2022, researchers at the University of Innsbruck succeeded in developing a universal qudit quantum processor with trapped ions.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] In the same year, researchers at Tsinghua University's Center for Quantum Information implemented the dual-type qubit scheme in trapped ion quantum computers using the same ion species.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] In 2025, the Innsbruck team managed to simulate two-dimensional lattice gauge theories on their qudit quantum computer.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Also in 2022, researchers at the University of California, Berkeley developed a technique to dynamically control the cross-Kerr interactions between fixed-frequency qutrits, achieving high two-qutrit gate fidelities.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] This was followed by a demonstration of extensible control of superconducting qudits up to $d=4$ in 2024 based on programmable two-photon interactions.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Similar to the qubit, the qutrit is the unit of quantum information that can be realized in suitable 3-level quantum systems.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] This is analogous to the unit of classical information trit of ternary computers.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Besides the advantage associated with the enlarged computational space, the third qutrit level can be exploited to implement efficient compilation of multi-qubit gates.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Any two-level quantum-mechanical system can be used as a qubit.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Multilevel systems can be used as well, if they possess two states that can be effectively decoupled from the rest (e.g., the ground state and first excited state of a nonlinear oscillator).
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Several physical implementations that approximate two-level systems to various degrees have been successfully realized.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] All physical implementations are affected by noise.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] The so-called *T*1 lifetime and *T*2 dephasing time are a time to characterize the physical implementation and represent their sensitivity to noise.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] A higher time does not necessarily mean that one or the other qubit is better suited for quantum computing, as gate times and fidelities also need to be considered.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Different applications like quantum sensing, quantum computing and quantum communication use different implementations of qubits to suit their application.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] The following is an incomplete list of physical implementations of qubits, and the choices of basis are by convention only.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] In 2008 a team of scientists from the U.K. and U.S. reported the first relatively long (1.75 seconds) and coherent transfer of a superposition state in an electron spin "processing" qubit to a nuclear spin "memory" qubit.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] This event can be considered the first relatively consistent quantum data storage, a vital step towards the development of quantum computing.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] In 2013, a modification of similar systems (using charged rather than neutral donors) has dramatically extended this time, to 3 hours at very low temperatures and 39 minutes at room temperature.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] Room temperature preparation of a qubit based on electron spins instead of nuclear spin was also demonstrated by a team of scientists from Switzerland and Australia.
[src:quantum-computing/qubit] An increased coherence of qubits is being explored by researchers who are testing the limitations of a Ge hole spin-orbit qubit structure.
